editors note: moscow chief of bureau michael putzel accompanied soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev on his trip last week to yugoslavia and reports on the differences between the two communist countries
in a downtown high-tech shop, a hungarian computer is connected to a japanese monitor and an american printer. western news magazines virtually unatainable in moscow are sold openly at newsstands
it's typical of accommodations yugoslavia has made as it looked both east and west in building a nonaligned communist nation
during a visit to three yugoslav cities last week, soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev was introduced to contrasts between socialist societies in yugoslavia and the soviet union, which has developed in relative isolation from the west
in the heavily roman catholic city of ljubljana, people rise to the clanging of church bells
the the ruling yugoslav league of communists, like the soviet communist party, is officially atheist, but the roman catholic and orthodox churches operate openly with little interference from authorities. in contrast, religious practice in the soviet union is severely restricted, and the state long ago seized most church property
kiosks throughout yugoslavia display and sell both domestic and foreign publications. brassy color photos on foreign erotic magazines that are banned in the soviet union share newsstand windows with tracts on marxism
the free-wheeling local press, ostensibly under the thumb of government and party officials, is less inhibited than the most avant-garde soviet publications, testing ``glasnost,'' or the policy of opennness pushed by gorbachev
shops in belgrade sell a wide array consumer goods and gadgets, and farmers' markets during the winter show off fresh fruits and vegetables that haven't been seen in moscow for months
in yugoslavia there are no apparent shortages, in contrast to moscow where long lines form on the street at the first hint of something desirable _ like egyptian oranges or shoes from yugoslavia
in slovenia, the prosperous northern republic gorbachev visited, most lines seem to be for state lottery tickets
private restaurants abound in yugoslavia, competing for customers with attentive service and local and foreign specialties. in the soviet union, such restaurants, known as cooperatives, only started springing up in the last year
mcdonald's is scheduled to open its first outlet in the communist world in downtown belgrade this week. crowds already gather at the door of a neatly renovated old building to examine the signs depicting a big mac, french fries and other fare more familiar in the west
the hamburger chain has been negotiating with the soviets for years but has so far been unable to satisfy itself that stores in the soviet union could maintain quality control. and there remain sticky questions about how western investors could take their profits out of the country
a holiday inn sign on a modern hotel in downtown ljubljana attests to the yugoslavs' ability to make joint ventures work
the soviets usually trade oil and other raw materials for prized finished goods from yugoslavia, such as shoes, clothing, furniture and machine tools
yugoslavs speak enthusiastically about their freedom to travel abroad, a privilege accorded few soviet citizens
many yugoslavs have visited relatives in the united states. more than 1 million work abroad either because they could not find work at home or can get more lucrative jobs elsewhere
the flight of growing numbers of workers is but one indication this socialist society is struggling with some problems of its own, such as 15 percent unemployment, triple-digit inflation and a $20 billion foreign debt
typical of price increases announced almost daily, the airport tax in belgrade doubled the day gorbachev left
on a street just off the main downtown square in belgrade, a white-bearded old man rummaged through a trash bin. a despairing yugoslav observer said such scenes have grown increasingly common in recent years as the nation's economic crisis has dragged living standards down from the boom years of the 1960s and early '70s
just outside the gates of a sleek modern factory gorbachev visited in slovenia, one of the most prosperous regions in the communist world, a pathetic shantytown bore grim testament to the inequality that persists, even in this socialist society
gorbachev, a peasant's son, might find such deprivation all too familiar. but the adriatic might also have reminded him of home. the route to dubrovnik was reminiscent of the beautiful coastal drive to the crimean resort of yalta or the black sea tourist mecca of sochi in gorbachev's native southern russia
the craggy coastlines are similar in all three places, lined with cyprus and palm trees and defined by dramatic drops to lapping seas
but in dubrovnik, the stickers on the windows of every boutique and shop inviting visitors to pay with western credit cards is an unfamiliar sight to the soviet visitor
passengers on two flights to xinjiang, china's northwesternmost province, reported ufo sightings, an official report said sunday
the state-run xinhua news agency said a passenger on a flight from beijing to urumqi, the provincial capital, last friday sighted the unidentified flying object to the right in front of the plane at 9:35 p.m
when the flight crew contacted local airports, they were told there was no plane in the area at that time
the object was described as being about the size of a basketball and sending out a beam like a searchlight. the crew sent a light signal to the object, which was flying opposite the plane, but received no response, xinhua said
three minutes later, the object changed directions and headed north, then split into two, with a smaller ball above a bean-shaped object. they were spinning at high speeds and gave off a ring of green light, the news agency said
by 9:48 p.m., the objects had disappeared, according to the crew
half an hour later, passengers aboard a flight from canton to urumqi spotted the ufo over the same area in western xinjiang, xinhua said
president corazon aquino said sunday that she does not plan to seek re-election in 1992 and told a radio audience that she lacks political ambition
mrs. aquino also announced on her weekly radio show that four manila policemen would answer charges before the human rights commission that they tortured captured communist rebels
asked by a caller about her plans to seek a second six-year term, mrs. aquino responded, ``i said earlier that i had no political ambitions and i feel i really was meant for one term
and so one term it will be,'' she said. ``but i want to thank the filipino people for having given me this opportunity to serve you at such a difficult time
i was only meant for transition. even now i consider this the transition period from dictatorship to full democracy,'' she said
mrs. aquino said the ``pillars of democracy'' _ the executive, legislative and judicial branches of the american-style government _ are already in place in the philippines
but because of the economic problems there is no full democracy because we must also have economic freedom,'' she said
mrs. aquino was swept to power in february 1986 by a popular revolt that ended president ferdinand marcos' 20-year authoritarian rule. both she and marcos claimed to have won the fraud-tainted presidential election earlier that month
mrs. aquino said in response to another question that four western district police officers would testify before the government human rights commission, but did not specify when this would be
the commission is merely an investigatory body, but it could make its evidence available to a court of law if it finds wrongdoing
she said commission chairwoman mary concepcion bautista ``has looked into the matter of recently captured communist insurgents.''
authorities rounded up two dozen suspected communist rebels last month in sweeps throughout the capital. seven were released for lack of evidence and 17 remain in custody
shortly after their capture, some of the detainees claimed they had been tortured. three of them appeared before the house of representatives' human rights committee and displayed marks on their bodies they said were the result of torture
the committee chairwoman, rep. nikki coeseteng, later told reporters the panel had found evidence of human rights abuse by the military, and called the treatment given the detainees ``inhuman.''
earlier this month, the london-based amnesty international and the local task force detainees charged there were widespread human rights abuses in the philippines
the church-backed task force said its investigation showed 7,444 filipinos were arrested illegally in 1987, eclipsing the 5,967 arrests in 1985 when marcos was president. it said many of those arrested last year were tortured
mrs. aquino called the amnesty report one-sided, and said the body had relied on task force for its information. she urged the two groups to bring their evidence to the rights commission
communist party chief zhao ziyang urged faster and bolder reforms of china's government and economy in a major speech published sunday, making clear his opposition to recent calls for caution
the speech was zhao's last salvo before china's parliament, the national people's congress, begins a session friday during which opposing views are expected to be aired
the head of the national people's congress, peng zhen, and the head of government, acting premier li peng, both are more conservative than zhao in their approach to reforming china's centralized economy and inefficient bureaucracy
zhao urged increasing incentives to foreign businesses to trade and invest in china, a thorough shake-up of the sluggish government bureaucracy, more competition among factories and more openness in party and state affairs
in the speech's only reference to opposition, zhao said the party ``demands that all communist party members working in the state council, especially high-ranking officials, should contribute their bit in the reform.'' the state council is china's cabinet
the speech was delivered to the party's 175-member central committee, which ended a five-day meeting saturday. the official xinhua news agency published a lengthy summary of the speech but did not say what day it was delivered
chinese incomes have more than doubled in the 10 years since senior leader deng xiaoping began the campaign to decentralize the economy and government and restore market forces and economic incentives
no top officials openly criticize the reforms, but some conservatives have emphasized the need to move slowly
among them is li peng, who has emphasized the need to control inflation and other ills triggered by the reforms. li is expected to be confirmed as premier at the national party congress
in a speech marking the lunar new year on feb. 17, li said the government may expand its subsidies of major commodities in order to reduce inflation, which hit 7.5 percent nationally last year but reached 19 percent in some cities
such a move would be a dramatic reversal of zhao's program to gradually reduce subsidies and allow supply and demand to set prices
in his central committee speech, zhao called for continuing price reform and said higher food prices would send a signal to farmers to produce more
some officials have indirectly criticized the reforms by warning about growing materialism in china and corruption among government and party workers
zhao acknowledged the problem and called for closer supervision of government employees and regular wage increases so they will be less tempted to engage in extortion
said zhao: ``communists should be the first to be concerned about their country and people and the last to enjoy themselves.''
