the fourth parliament in bangladesh's 17-year history was sworn in sunday, but allegations of a rigged election raise doubts about the legitimacy of the lawmaking body
parliament speaker huda choudhury gave the oath of office to the new members, although the 18 members of the combined opposition party failed to attend the ceremony. there was no immediate explanation for their absence
despite its name, the opposition bloc consists of 76 small parties loyal to the government of president hussain muhammad ershad
the parliament was chosen march 3 in an election where there was much evidence of vote tampering and little of voter turnout, despite the government's claim that more than 50 percent of voters took part
opposition parties boycotted the polling and charged that fewer than 1 percent of voters cast ballots
no parliament in bangladesh ever has served its full five-year term. the previous one, elected in 1986, was dissolved by ershad last dec. 6 in a move to compromise with opposition parties demanding the president's ouster
the main opposition coalition of 21 parties denounced the move, however, and boycotted the elections, saying fair elections under ershad were impossible
ershad's jatiya party won 251 of the 300 seats. the national socialist party got three, the freedom party two, and independent candidates won 25 seats. election for one seat was postponed after a candidate was slain
the president told a religious gathering on march 13 that he would offer legislation to amend the constitution to make bangladesh an islamic state. the country's population is more than 90 percent moslem
ershad's party could easily adopt such legislation, having well over the needed two-thirds majority in the parliament
but the opposition parties _ still carrying out a four-month campaign of strikes and rallies to oust ershad _ already have announced they will oppose the move
even the leader of the fundamentalist moslem party jamaat-e-islami, abbas ali khan, denounced the proposal. ``this is a political gimmick by ershad to perpetuate his rule,'' he said
ershad, a former general, has vowed not to resign. he took power in a bloodless coup in 1982 and was elected in 1986 in a vote that the opposition claims was rigged
bangladesh became an independent state in 1971 after a civil war with pakistan
u.s. envoy philip habib arrived in jordan on sunday for talks on the u.s. plan for peace in the middle east after meeting with officials in egypt, where he said negotiations went well
habib met with egyptian president hosni mubarak in cairo and later told reporters the talks were ``extraordinarily good,'' egypt's state-run middle east news agency reported
his tour also will take him to saudi arabia and morocco
high-ranking jordanian officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said habib would meet with king hussein and other officials. but they noted that jordan would not deliver an immediate response to the u.s. proposals
jordanian officials also have said recently that the government was unlikely to respond to the proposals for about another week
habib's mission is a follow-up to a tour by u.s. secretary of state george p. shultz, who shuttled among egypt, jordan, israel and syria in early march to pitch the american peace plan for the 40-year old arab-israeli conflict
the plan calls for a three-year period of self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians living in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip. negotiations on the final status of the occupied territories would start in december
mubarak has called the plan encouraging, but suggested, without going into specifics, that some of its provisions be ``developed.''
habib was quoted by the middle east news agency as saying u.s. officials had emphasized that the plan ``would not be altered or cut up.''
state department spokesman charles redman said in washington on friday that habib would solicit the views of leaders of the four countries on his itinerary and would also brief them on talks this week in washington between administration officials and israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir
some years ago, rating the nation's federal judges, american lawyer magazine praised the ``mental strength'' of gerhard a. gesell, but took off points because his ``arrogance is offensive to many attorneys.''
as a judge who has dealt with watergate and other highly publicized cases in his 20 years on the bench, 77-year-old gesell is on the hot seat again. he was hand-picked by the capital's chief federal judge to try former national security adviser john m. poindexter, lt. col. oliver l. north, and two arms dealers in the iran-contra affair
american lawyer found gesell ``widely regarded as the most agile and powerful mind on the d.c. bench,'' but it also had ``a suspicion that he is too sure of his own abilities; that he is perhaps overbearing.''
few lawyers who ever appeared before gesell would disagree with those assessments. gesell is tough. he was once described by a washington columnist as having ``a rosy troll-king's face,'' but more often than not it's that of a storm king
such things are not said publicly, but the probability is gesell was tapped because he is the most likely to get the job done swiftly and cleanly. it will be up to gesell to decide the politically absorbing question of the trial's timing. before the november election or afterward? before reagan leaves office or after?
gesell is the emperor of his courtroom. he makes things move. long-winded lawyers quickly learn to change their ways
when he is displeased, everyone knows it
gesell conducted the 1974 ``plumbers'' trial in which john d. ehrlichman, the former presidential domestic adviser, was convicted of violating the rights of a psychiatrist by sending white house agents to burglarize his office
ehrlichman found gesell ``obviously hostile.'' he wrote later that ``a number of spectators at that trial gave us affidavits describing gesell's facial reactions and gestures, which seemed intended to indicate to the jury how he felt about me and my attorneys.''
gesell called the case ``a shameful episode in the history of our country.'' and he expressed a sentiment that may come into play in the iran-contra trial: ``it is impossible to preserve freedom anywhere when zealots take over and the rule of law is ignored.''
four years ago, gesell had a case that involved the language in the law that governs how federal commissions operate. ``another example of unimpressive legislative drafting,'' he grumped. ``the courts do not welcome their role in such disputes,'' he said
in 1980, gesell ruled that the air force was wrong in ousting a decorated vietnam veteran because he was a homosexual. gesell accused the service of perverse behavior
but three years earlier, he had dismissed the suit of another acknowledged homosexual to be reinstated to the service. gesell concluded that ``an individual's right to privacy does not extend to homosexual conduct even when it occurs in private between consenting adults.''
gesell is among a generation of americans whose parents used the book ``the child from five to ten'' as a guide to bringing them up. in his case, however, the teaching was more direct: the author was his father, noted yale child psychologist and pediatrician arnold gesell
a yale graduate himself, gesell made a name as an antitrust lawyer with covington &amp; burling, one of washington's most renowned law firms. he was named to the federal bench in 1968 by president lyndon b. johnson
he quickly developed a reputation as one of the most scholarly judges in the courthouse
gesell's opinions have ranged widely: in 1970 he ordered the house internal security committee not to publish a report that listed 65 people as radical campus speakers. it was a landmark decision limiting congressional power
in 1968, he broadened the district of columbia's law to permit abortions virtually at a physician's discretion. the ruling was reversed by the supreme court
and in 1971 he ruled that the washington post could publish the pentagon papers study on the origins of the vietnam war, saying ``there is no proof that there will be a definite break in diplomatic relations, that there will be an armed attack on the united states ... or on an ally, that there will be war.''
outside toilets, cornmeal for dinner and police visits in the middle of the night gave 170 white christians a taste of everyday life in this black township
the event, designed to bring whites and blacks together and break down apartheid barriers, was organized by two christian groups and ended sunday with an emotional church service at a ymca hall
hundreds of worshipers clasped hands and swayed in rhythm to hymns of christian fellowship. said the rev. nico smith, one of the encounter's organizers: ``i thank god that this is still possible in south africa.''
on saturday night, while soldiers checked cars entering the township a few hundred yards away, the black hosts and their white guests barbecued sausage and dipped cornmeal from a huge iron pot while discussing the four-day encounter at a picnic
ten years ago if we did this the police would have just come and chased all the blacks away,'' said smith
murray hofmeyr, 29, a white theology student, was asked repeatedly to tell how police had come to the door at 3:30 a.m. friday to arrest him and his host, black churchworker sandy lebese. he said they refused to say why and ``were very rude.''
police freed hofmeyr a few hours later ``when i finally convinced them what was going on, that there were 170 white people staying in the township that night. they didn't believe me.''
lebese, who was imprisoned from 1977 to 1983 on a sabotage conviction, remained in detention without explanation
another delegate, nick paton, grandson of novelist alan paton, said police came to his door, also, at 2:30 a.m., asking what he was doing in the township
it's not normal to see a white man putting up in a black house,'' said one of the hosts, joe sekese, who was not surprised by the police action. ``i think it's a breakthrough, because in fact, i expected something tragic to happen, that the soldiers would break up the whole thing.''
smith, a white dutch reformed minister who moved into mamelodi with government permission two years ago, said he believed the police action ``was just the way they harass you, to let you know they're there, in control.''
but hofmeyr said he thought police were looking for a white man they believed responsible for a car-bombing thursday 20 miles southwest of pretoria
jacques bosch, 11, spent four days playing with 12-year-old mandla mabena as their parents tried to get to know each other
mandla's mother, betty, who works as a maid in a white home in pretoria, said she was worred about having a white woman come to her house as a guest. she said her employers ``treat me like family,'' but they have never been to her home
i was concerned about what food to serve, what beddings i had,'' said mrs. mabena
some delegates stayed in typical four-room township homes, with a toilet in the yard, a zinc basin to bathe in, and not enough beds to go around. others stayed in the more modern homes that the government and private industry are building to combat political unrest
some of the worst violence of the past three years occurred in mamelodi, and soldiers still patrol the streets
most of my black friends are ... mostly radical people fighting for a better south africa, fighting their bitterness. it was an experience to see the peace and quiet here,'' said annemarie bosch
when guests took their hosts out for dinner friday night, some reported rude comments and noticed stares from other diners in the restaurants. most said they had no trouble
the delegates, including about 40 blacks who stayed in white homes in pretoria, tried to adopt a joint statement at the end of the encounter that would reflect their mutual experience, but found they could not
apartheid was very successful,'' said smith. ``it succeeded to divide the people, to separate them from one another. it eventually ended up with the whites fearing the blacks and the blacks being furious with the whites, and you know anger and fear is a recipe for violence.''
smith promoted a separate message from the whites to tell other whites what they had learned and urge an end to ``this forced separation'' of the races under apartheid
david ramakgadi, a church field worker, read the blacks' statement: ``we are thrilled that at last, after a struggle of more than 50 years, you have come to our township not to tell us, but to listen. we see our communities as schools to educate people about the need to liberate south africa.''
under apartheid, south africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
a 24-hour telephone line set up to field questions about aids has been averaging 100 calls daily in its first week of operation, a newspaper reported sunday
most callers want to know how the virus can be transmitted and ways to prevent it, dr. doyin odupe, president of the nigeria council on aids education, which runs the national hot line, was quoted in the lagos concord newspaper as saying
nigeria, with an estimated 100 million people, has only 20 known cases of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
it is spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant women to their offspring
