emergency action by federal regulators to stabilize two big banking companies hit by deposit runs is sure to revive charges of a double standard for dealing with ailing financial institutions
while small banks are closing at a rate unseen since the great depression, the government, in effect, has declared large banks too big to fail, the critics say
the best known example of the ``too-big-to-fail syndrome'' is continental illinois corp., which in 1984 required $4.5 billion in the largest-ever government bailout
the federal deposit insurance corp., the agency that insures deposits in commercial banks, hopes to recover all but $1.7 billion of that by selling its stake in continental. but nearly four years after the bailout, the fdic is still the major stockholder in the bank
two government moves last week to prop up institutions nearly identical in size to continental are renewing concerns
the fdic on thursday pumped $1 billion into first republicbank corp. of dallas, which has lost nearly $2 billion in deposits since the start of the year. with $33.2 billion in assets, it is the nation's 13th largest commercial bank holding company
the agency also promised to protect all depositors and general creditors of the company's 73 subsidiary banks
the federal home loan bank board, which regulates savings institutions, made a similar pledge on friday regarding the $33.7 billion financial corp. of america, owner of the stockton, calif.,-based american savings &amp; loan association
the second largest thrift holding company in the country, fca had lost $493 million in deposits in january and february. its request for $1.5 billion in assistance is under review
the eventual price tag of solving the problems at first republicbank and fca isn't known for certain, but analysts believe the bailouts ultimately could rival, and possibly even surpass, the continental illinois rescue
the promises made by the fdic and bank board go beyond the agencies' normal practice. usually, deposit accounts are protected only to $100,000, and creditors are not protected at all
when smaller banks fail, as 184 did last year, the fdic pays off depositors up to the insurance limit or arranges for the accounts to be transferred to a solvent institution
big banks, with their extensive ties to other banks, present a more complicated problem. the failure of a large institution could cause a chain reaction of insolvencies at smaller banks and end up costing the fdic more than the amount needed to keep the big bank operating
using government aid to entice private investors to take over an ailing institution also is often cheaper than a straight payoff of depositors
that logic doesn't make it any easier for executives who watch their small banks go under while their colleagues at large institutions stay in business
beyond the big bank-small bank double standard, there is what some regard as a dual standard in dealing with large regional banks like first republicbank and the even bigger money center banks deeply involved with shaky loans to third world countries
paul getman, a financial economist with the wefa group, a philadelphia consulting firm, said bankers at the large regional institutions, whose loans are in real estate and energy, believe regulators are much more reluctant to force money center banks to write down the value of overseas loans
texas bankers feel ... the fdic is not clamping down as hard on new york city banks because the nature of their bad loans is such that they can get away with saying they're worth 50 cents on the dollar, for example,'' getman said
there's a lot of political play (in how loans to third world countries are valued), whereas everyone knows that loans on texas real estate are worth 15 cents on the dollar,'' he said
rep. ferdnand g. st germain, d-r.i., chairman of the house banking committee, said he plans hearings this spring on the criteria used to decide ``who survives and who fails among the troubled institutions.''
st germain has voiced concern in the past about ``sweet fail-safe deals for private investors.''
fdic chairman l. william seidman, however, has pointed out that government bank rescues bail out depositors, usually not stockholders, corporate debt holders or management
bert ely, a private financial institutions analyst in alexandria, va., defended bailouts as saving money for the insurance funds, which are funded by premiums paid by banks and savings and loans and ultimately backed by the taxpayer
ely argued that regulators ought to make bailouts far sooner than they usually do
the important thing is that they end the tragedy. ... every hour that goes by increases banks' losses and the losses (to the insurance funds). it is so critical to get that assistance in there and stop the bleeding right away,'' he said
dave skidmore covers banking and financial issues in washington for the associated press
liberal and conservative chinese leaders gather friday to wrangle over the future of the country's economic and political reforms in a congress that could reveal how deep divisions are between the camps
featured at the annual meeting of the national people's congress, china's parliament, will be communist party chief zhao ziyang, and acting premier li peng, who heads the conservatives
zhao, 69, the protege of semi-retired senior leader deng xiaoping, is the champion of rapid reform. in a speech published sunday, zhao urged faster and bolder reforms, making clear his opposition to recent calls for caution
li, 59, a soviet-educated engineer, is regarded as a cautious technocrat who supports the reforms but would limit their scope and slow their implementation
zhao was the star at a major party congress last fall that laid down guidelines for china into the 21st century. at the congress, however, li will be at center stage, delivering a key report at the opening of the three-week session that will define the nation's immediate goals
li is expected to sound several conservative themes _ that the government must pay more attention to the countryside following three straight disappointing grain harvests and that controlling double-digit inflation must take precedence over further reform of china's inefficient pricing system
analysts also will watch how much support li gives zhao's ambitious proposal to turn factories along china's coast into processing centers for exports. the plan is controversial because it would allow coastal regions to develop faster than china's vast interior
some observers say open disagreement between zhao and li is unlikely. both support china's economic changes, but they differ on the pace
five years ago you could talk about reformists and conservatives,'' said one asian diplomat. ``but today nobody would come out against reform.''
the first session of the 7th congress _ each congress sits for five years _ will be one of the busiest and most important in years. it will confirm li as premier, replace li xiannian as president and fill dozens of important government posts
the 2,970 delegates will approve a government reorganization in which several ministries are to merge or be eliminated. they also will amend the constitution to legalize private businesses and pass several laws
most important is the industrial enterprise law, which will give legal definition to the government's attempts to separate the functions of the owner _the state _ and the manager of businesses
factory managers will be given the right to run their plants without undue interference from government and party officials. they also will take responsibility for profits and losses
the congress will also vote to make southern china's hainan island, a focus of zhao's coastal development plans, a new province
the congress will also enact important personnel changes
several elderly leaders, who have opposed most economic reforms, will finally step down
but conservatives who favor cautious change, and not rapid reformers, will probably take their place
li, named acting premier when zhao was appointed head of the party last fall, will take over the post held for 27 years by his foster father, chou en-lai. he will also head the commission for restructuring the economy, giving him greater influence in determining, and possibly slowing, the course of reforms
li xiannian, 78, will end his five-year term in the largely ceremonial post of president, and is likely to replace deng yingchao, 84, chou en-lai's widow, as chairman of the chinese people's political consultative conference, an advisory body
tapped to be the next president is yang shangkun, 80, a senior military officer, member of the party politburo and friend to deng xiaoping
yao yilin, 71, a respected but somewhat conservative economist, is slated to head a powerful economic planning commission
the new defense minister, replacing 78-year-old zhang aiping, is expected to be qin jiwei, 74, former beijing military region commander and a politburo member
peng zhen, an 86-year-old conservative curmudgeon, will resign as chairman of the people's congress, with vice premier wan li a likely successor
dreaming of life in the circus, a handful of would-be big top stars practiced slapstick skits, laughed at pretend jokes and even took a shaving cream pie in the face at auditions for clown college
for two hours saturday, about 35 people _ including an actress, a singer, a history teacher and a retired dentist _ tested their mettle as clowns, vying to get into the school in venice, fla., dubbed the ``yale of yucks'' and the world's only institution of higher laughter
in order to be a good clown, you have to have a heart the size of alaska and be willing to give it away on a daily basis,'' said steve smith, director of the college run by ringling bros. and barnum &amp; bailey circus
you can't go out and flap your arms around and think that's clowning,'' smith told the clown hopefuls. ``you have to feel it and believe it.''
with a videotape camera rolling, smith tested the applicants' abilities in mime, acting movement and classic clown gags in a dance practice room at depaul university
competition to get into clown college is nearly as keen as for the ivy league
the school holds about 25 auditions a year around the country for a maximum of 60 openings. last year, 2,000 people applied to be trained as clowns and only 50 were accepted, smith said
to make the cuts, smith and ruth craddock, a teacher at the college, review audition videotapes and written applications submitted by the aspiring clowns
the clown candidates pantomimed different emotions, contorting their faces in anger, drooping in sadness and beaming with happiness. they acted out a simple slapstick skit and practiced laughing hysterically when a fellow auditioner pretended to tell a joke
we're giving a collective hug to 20,000 people (in the circus audience) and are trying to make them forget for two hours that the toilet won't flush, the bills are overdue and their kid needs braces,'' explained smith, wearing a clown suit of blue pants, rainbow suspenders, red polka-dot bow tie, yellow hair and red bulb nose
for those who are accepted, the 10-week program in such skills as stilt-walking, gymnastics and pantomime is free _ with a catch. the students must agree to join the ringling bros. circus as a clown if they are good enough
we think of it as boot camp for the circus,'' said smith, the former host of a children's television program in chicago. ``we're very serious about being silly.''
jason stern, a 46-year-old retired dentist who runs an international contracting business, tried out on his 23rd wedding anniversary because, he said, he harbors a secret desire to be a clown
i'm at that stage in life where i want to really enjoy myself,'' stern said. ``i'd drop everything i'm doing'' to join the circus
noah budin, a 27-year-old singer wearing a hawaiian shirt and a cleveland indians hat, said he has dreamed of working as a clown since his childhood
i've just never grown up,'' he said. ``i want to perform for people and make them laugh. ... i want to feel that power.''
we're not looking for people who can juggle and ride unicycles because we can teach that,'' said smith, who went through clown college in 1971 and has been its director since 1985. ``what i'm really looking for are people who have a sincere desire to learn the craft and who have a big heart.''
israelis strafed hills and combed the countryside in their deepest push into southern lebanon this year in an apparent effort to knock out guerrilla bases there, police said sunday
their troops, however, met no resistance saturday as they pressed north several miles beyond the eastern end of their buffer zone toward the shiite moslem village of maydoun, police said. they withdrew about four hours later
the ground assault followed increased guerrilla attacks on the security belt with soviet-made katyusha rockets. israel said it needed the buffer area to deter such attacks when it withdrew most troops from lebanon in june 1985 after its 1982 invasion and three-year occupation
the israelis and militiamen from the mainly christian south lebanon army fought a seven-hour artillery duel with shiite amal militiamen on saturday before moving north
amal said 10 militiamen from the south lebanon army were killed or hurt and one shiite fighter wounded in the exchanges engulfing the villages of mashgara and ein el-tineh near maydoun. police reported two civilians and a syrian soldier wounded
syria has 25,000 troops in lebanon under a 1976 arab league peacekeeping mandate. chief's yard</head>
two days after the police chief's father died, authorities began digging in the chief's front yard. they kept digging until they found a skeleton 20 feet down that turned out to be the first husband of the chief's current wife
no charges have been filed and authorities have released few details of their investigation
they have only confirmed, from dental records, that the skeleton was the remains of russell bean, and that he had been beaten on the head and chest with an unidentified object
bean was 25 when he was last seen in 1978. he and robert chambers, who became the part-time police chief three years ago, apparently met while working together at a factory in keene and became drinking buddies
after bean disappeared, chambers divorced his first wife and married bean's wife, sylvia, about 35
chambers, 36, and other members of the family have said nothing publicly about the case
chambers was part-time police chief in marlow and nearby gilsum; he has resigned the marlow job and taken indefinite leave from the gilsum post. he has also been suspended from the police force in winchester
his wife has left her job as a school-bus driver and their four children from former marriages have been taken out of school
chambers' former wife, deborah, living in jaffrey, was hospitalized while authorities were digging in chambers' yard; authorities won't say why or disclose her condition
the mystery began unfolding march 9 with the death of chambers' father, clifton chambers, 61
the keene sentinel reported that sources with detailed knowledge of the investigation said the elder chambers told his daughter melissa that bean died accidentally in a fist fight when he fell and hit his head on a rock, and that the elder chambers had helped bury him
melissa chambers reportedly told authorities the deathbed tale the next day, and the digging began march 11
on march 14, clifton chambers was buried. hours later, when the hole in robert chambers' yard was 20 feet deep and 25 feet in diameter, bean's skeleton was found
on thursday, march 17, it was determined bean had been beaten with a blunt object
chambers' lawyer, mark sisti of the public defender's office, said he could not answer questions about how the body came to be buried there or whether chambers knew. but he said, ``my client had nothing to do with causing the death of mr. bean.''
sisti filed a motion friday to gain access to documents that persuaded a judge to issue the search warrant that allowed authorities to dig up chambers' yard. ``a lot of reports have been generated through rumors and speculation and we'd like to see exactly what's in there,'' he said
the attorney general's office said it will try to keep the documents sealed
all that has left the 600 residents of the rural community in hilly southwestern new hampshire speculating on what happened. rumors spread rapidly from talk at the general store, at vic's, the only restaurant in town, or at private gatherings
mabel champney, who knew the elder chambers for 45 years and had been dating him the past three years since the death of his wife, emphatically rejected any thought that he would hide a crime
i don't think he knew a thing about it,'' she said. ``i don't think he would hold back anything if someone did something wrong.''
harry briggs, the elder chambers' brother-in-law, said melissa chambers was ``very bitter against bob,'' something that had ``built through the years. they always fought back and forth.''
bean helped chambers build the 1{-story cabin where he still lives, one town resident said. the house sits on two acres remaining from the 100 acres once owned by chambers' father
the union leader in manchester quoted people as saying chambers and his wife and bean and his wife were good friends
but then robert and deborah chambers separated in 1978 and divorced in june 1979
bean disappeared in september 1978, and sylvia bean won a divorce the next year. she and chambers were married in september 1979
chambers was a trainee and was ready to become a full-time policeman for winchester after passing a 10-week course at the state police academy, but the digging began the day he graduated
federal officials disappointed by lukewarm response to a year-long amnesty program for illegal aliens hope a blitz of sideshow-like hoopla in the final weeks will spark a last-minute flurry of interest
we are expecting to see a surge in applications,'' immigration and naturalization service spokesman vern jervis said in washington, d.c
our feeling is there has been a lot of procrastination. but we already have seen an increase in recent weeks, and we believe we will have good numbers between now and the end of the program as people realize time is getting short.''
the last day illegal aliens can apply for amnesty to legalize their presence in this country and permit them to seek citizenship is may 4. the program began may 5, 1987
after an initial surge that saw illegal aliens standing in long lines for hours at ins centers around the country, interest tapered off substantially
when the amnesty program started, officials estimated there were between 4 million and 6 million illegal aliens in the united states and that between 2 million and 4 million might apply for amnesty
through march 16, the latest date for which figures were available, 1.39 million undocumented aliens had applied for amnesty, jervis said
critics claim the government mismanaged the amnesty program by failing to adequately publicize it and failing to overcome illegal aliens' ingrained distrust of the ins, perceived in the past only as the agency that wanted to hunt them down and deport them
in recent weeks, ins officials have waged aggressive programs to spread the message that the amnesty program will end soon
we have done everything except stand on our heads,'' said william king, who oversees the amnesty program for the ins western region, including california, arizona, nevada, hawaii and guam
the efforts have ranged from sponsoring old-fashioned neighborhood block parties and participating in ethnic parades to speaking to community groups, at catholic masses in the southwest and west and baptist services in the south, and on radio talks shows nationwide
some of the more unusual schemes include stuffing messages about the deadline inside packages of tortillas and in fortune cookies
critics point out that most fortune cookies are eaten by middle-class caucasians
ins workers also have donned sombreros at hispanic festivities, hugged babies at chinese, korean and southeast asian gatherings, and swaddled themselves in polynesian costumes and roasted pigs at ``tongan night'' parties. they have tried to reach sports fans by hiring planes trailing amnesty messages to fly over stadiums and have flashed messages on electronic stadium signboards
in mcallen, texas, ins worker art zuniga wrote a song in spanish entitled ``amnistia'' and persuaded local radio stations to play it often. in some neighborhoods, boy scouts have been enlisted to go door-to-door handing out leaflets
in recent weeks, ins officials with much fanfare staged ceremonies to present temporary residency permits, commonly known as ``green cards,'' to a 98-year-old woman in texas and a 101-year-old man in california. in each case, the person was billed as the oldest undocumented alien to receive legal status
in other nations where similar amnesty programs have been offered, 10 percent of all applications came on the last day, not unlike the way people file their tax returns, king said
if that happens, we're going to be out there with mail bags accepting applications until 11:59 p.m., may 4,'' king said
to make it easier for people to get amnesty, the ins announced friday it would accept applications that are simply filled out and signed by may 4. those applying will have an additional 60 days to supply the documentation required to suport the applications
under the immigration reform and control act of 1986, illegal aliens who have lived in this country continuously since before jan. 1, 1982, are eligible to seek amnesty. the process costs applicants $185 per person up to a maximum of $420 per family, plus a $75 counseling fee and a $10 photo and fingerprint fee
the recent nato summit in brussels proved that the western alliance is trying to unilaterally disarm the soviet union so it can achieve military superiority, a top soviet general said in an article published sunday
gen. sergei akhromeyev, chief of the general staff of the soviet armed forces, said in the defense ministry newspaper, krasnaya zvezda, that nato was unreasonably seeking cuts in soviet conventional military forces
one draws an absolutely definite conclusion that the nato leadership is trying to impose unilateral disarmament upon socialist countries, to break the existing structure of the soviet general-purpose forces and in the final account, attain military superiority,'' akhromeyev said
a march 3 declaration by leaders of north atlantic treaty organization countries called for cuts in soviet conventional military forces. nato says the soviet-led warsaw pact has a 2-1 advantage in tanks and artillery
but akhromeyev reiterated the soviet view that nato and the warsaw pact are roughly equal in strength. while nato calls for a reduction in tanks and artillery, it is superior in aircraft and sea power, the general said
akhromeyev also criticized nato for refusing to link conventional arms and reduction or elimination of tactical, or long-range, nuclear missiles
the soviet union is willing to meet the west halfway, ``but its initiatives should be reciprocated by the other side. it is just a waste of time to demand unilateral disarmament from the ussr,'' he said
nato has not directly responded to a warsaw pact proposal made in june 1986 for a comprehensive plan to cut military forces throughout europe, from the atlantic ocean to the soviet union's ural mountains, he said
michael dukakis, chatting with laid-off steelworkers on chicago's east side, was munching on a big, messy danish pastry. but _ not wanting to get his breakfast all over his crisp business suit _ he was eating it with a spoon, to the amusement of the rough-hewn onlookers
this prim approach illustrated what the democratic presidential candidate from massachusetts freely admitted to chicagoans in a campaign ad narrated by bricklayers union chief tommy mcintyre: ``he's not your shot-and-beer kind of guy.''
but in the course of dukakis' campaign, it's often been easier to figure out what kind of a guy dukakis isn't than what kind he is
in iowa, dukakis crusaded against aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels. in new hampshire, he pushed his opposition to the seabrook nuclear plant. and he spoke out against space-based missile defenses and additions to a navy carrier task force
but in the south, dukakis said he would fight communist aggression in central america, and he reminded voters that he has cut taxes and kept the state budget balanced
in illinois, he portrayed himself as a friend to labor while largely steering clear of substantive issues. instead, he spoke about the need to pick a candidate who can win in november
the multiple portraits of the massachusetts governor reflect a conscious campaign strategy to seek the broadest support possible. in some ways it has paid off
on super tuesday, for example, dukakis won in all regions of the country. and although he finished third in illinois last week, dukakis did equally well among liberals, moderates and conservatives, according to exit polls
when nbc news asked illinois voters which democratic candidate was more conservative, the choices included tennessee sen. albert gore and missouri rep. richard gephardt. on the most-liberal list were jesse jackson and illinois sen. paul simon. only one candidiate was on both lists _ michael dukakis
dukakis has to have some image,'' said pollster sheldon gawiser. ``is he tough? i don't know. is he compassionate? i don't know. is he new? i don't know. is he old? i don't know.''
dukakis has promised not to reduce spending on social programs and to increase college scholarship programs for needy high school graduates. he wants a $500 million ``partnership'' between the public and private sectors to invest in economically depressed areas. he talks about protecting the environment
more often, though, dukakis has stuck to a generalized stump speech that only touches lightly on his policy views. his super tuesday victory speech, delivered in chicago, was filled with phrases like, ``you don't have to be from chicago to want a president who will make america no. 1 again,'' and ``the best america isn't behind us; the best america is yet to come.''
even in massachusetts, where dukakis has been in public life as a legislator and governor for 25 years, labels don't stick fast to dukakis, because his positions don't fit conventional pigeonholes
dukakis was a reform-minded liberal when he first won the governorship in 1974. he succeeded a popular republican chief executive and inherited an enormous budget deficit
those deficits forced dukakis to break his promise of no new taxes, a move some believe cost him his job four years later. yet he also lost liberal support in that same race because he approved reuctions in welfare benefits
1978 was ...the turning point in his political life,'' wrote robert turner and charles kenney in their recent biography of the governor. ``political pragmatism dictated what changed. it was not an alteration in character, but a shift in style, approach _ a change he had to make if he was to be successful again in politics.''
what dukakis calls ``an involuntary four-year sabbatical'' at harvard's kennedy school of government kept him in touch with massachusetts politics and exposed him to a pool of talent that he has since tapped for his presidential campaign. the governor's staff is dotted with former students and faculty members from the kennedy school
in 1982, dukakis defeated arch-rival gov. edward king in a bruising campaign in which dukakis made it clear he considered the king administration corrupt
his second term was marked by its pragmatism and emphasis on encouraging business expansion. the four years between 1982 and 1986 found dukakis facing protests from welfare recipients who claimed their benefits kept them far below the poverty level and from gays and lesbians who accused him of discriminating against homosexuals by forbidding them from being foster parents
in the south, dukakis, addressing his image as a cool problem-solver, commented a tag many have been eager to pin on him
i have a defintion of a technocrat,'' he said. ``a liberal who can balance a budget.'' attention</head>
texas playwright larry l. king is scratching his beard in puzzlement
his blockbuster musical, ``the best little whorehouse in texas,'' ran on broadway for 1,588 performances to rave reviews, spawned four national touring companies, played on four continents, became a hit movie and has grossed more than $175 million at last count
but when he mailed the script of his latest play, ``the night hank williams died,'' to a big new york producer, it was returned a week later stamped ``unsolicited materials not accepted.''
other producers and theater directors responded with polite yawns, broken promises, excuses or no response at all
ford's theater in washington didn't bother to acknowledge receipt of his manuscript
perhaps i should have sent them `the night abe lincoln died,''' king says
after investing four years and an estimated $7,000 in travel, phone calls, postage, script copying and lawyers' fees, king finally got his play on the boards at washington's small, financially struggling new playwrights' theater, where it finished a successful five-week run in early march
it's something of a humbling and perplexing experience for king, who already has 11 books, five stage plays, four television documentaries, hundreds of magazine articles, a tv emmy and nominations for tony and national book awards to his credit
but the playwright shrugs off suggestions that new playwrights' was a humiliating comedown after the bright lights of broadway
during the day, king hustled tickets by phone and delivered show posters to swank downtown restaurants where his pals dined without him
on arriving at the 125-seat theater near dupont circle, his first job was to wash coffee cups for the cast and crew. then he donned costume and makeup to perform a starring role in his own play, seven times a week
king has concluded that getting plays produced anywhere in america is ``a perpetual crapshoot,'' no matter how famous the playwright
this is not as good as billy dick's stuff,'' king said in a recent interview, using his down-home nickname for william shakespeare. ``but i know this is not a bad play.''
the critics agree. and a new playwrights' spokeswoman, paige gold, said ``it was the biggest ticket-seller we've had this season.''
the night hank williams died'' is not a play about the legendary country western singer. it's about the death of ``a dreamer in a dreamless land,'' a former high school football star named thurmond stottle who's pumping gas in a small west texas town, working on a beer gut and desperate to escape
king tells the tale, both funny and sad, with dialogue as hot and spicy as three-alarm chili and the indisputable truth of a man who's been there himself. unlike stottle, who was gunned down before he could flee with his guitar and his dream of singing fame in nashville, tenn., king made good his escape from west texas
he began his writing career as a reporter on a string of small newspapers in texas and new mexico before he moved to washington in 1954 as a congressional aide. while working for rep. jim wright, d-texas, now house speaker, king finished his first book, a political novel titled ``the one-eyed man.''
today, while trying to arrange future engagements for ``hank williams'' in texas theaters and a possible off-broadway run this fall, king is finishing his 12th book, a largely autobiographical anti-war novel called ``war movies.''
at the same time, he's working on another play, ``the golden shadows old west museum,'' which is tentatively scheduled to premiere next season at the arkansas repertory theater in little rock
it's a helluva hard way to make a living,'' said king, 59, as he lit another cigarette and brushed his blue jeans in the den of his comfortable home in a wooded section of northwest washington
because of enormous production costs and limited financial resources, he says, most theaters play it safe in favor of proven hits. ``there just aren't that many theaters willing to do new plays,'' he said
he finds it ``very peculiar'' that the author of the wildly successful ``whorehouse'' would have so much difficulty finding a producer for his new play, even in texas where he is immensely popular
all i can figure is those folks don't have much imagination,'' he said. ``when you send in your manuscripts, you just don't hear from theaters. i don't know if they open their mail or even see it. that's not good manners, much less good business.''
after five years of debate about futuristic space weapons, both supporters and critics of president reagan's star wars system agree that the program will remain one of reagan's chief legacies after he leaves office next year
there is no way this program will die when reagan leaves office, regardless of who is elected in november,'' said john pike of the federation of american scientists, a chief critic of reagan's program
there's a constituency for the program now and that means it is here to stay,'' pike said. ``the next president, whether republican or democrat, is going to have limited options. he won't be able to significantly raise it because of budget restrictions, but he won't be able to cut it deeply, either.''
rep. les aspin, d-wis., chairman of the house armed services committee and another critic of the missile defense system, agreed. ``politically, the star wars issue is here to stay. it's not going to go away,'' aspin said
and on the other side, retired air force gen. daniel graham, who is one of reagan's strongest supporters, said, ``i believe that it is almost inexorable that the program will continue to grow. the debate has been changed.''
we are making progress. the debate now is about what kind of system, not whether any defense at all is a good idea,'' said air force lt. gen. james abrahamson, head of the program
the debate began almost as soon as reagan proposed the idea five years ago at the end of a nationally televised speech. in the speech, reagan referred to the current nuclear doctrine of mutual assured destruction, which holds that each superpower is deterred from a nuclear attack against the other because of the threat of devastating retaliation
science, reagan said, should be devoted to defense, not offense, and he laid out his dream of building a defensive system that would ``free the world from the threat of nuclear war.''
reagan dubbed his plan the strategic defense initiative (sdi), although pike and other critics began calling it ``star wars,'' after the hit movie, a name that stuck
one of the strongest supporters of the program was graham, head of a private foundation known as high frontier, and the chief advocate of deploying a system of orbiting ``garages'' full of rockets that could be readily fired at attacking soviet missiles
the united states had been devoting hundreds of millions of dollars to defensive research before reagan's speech, but the president's interest changed the program and set off a national debate about whether such a system could be built and what it would cost
originally, pentagon officials said the program would look at a variety of exotic, futuristic weapons, such as neutral particle beams, electromagnetic rail guns and electron lasers
but many of those technologies have not panned out and while research on them is continuing, the program is now concentrating almost half its $4.2 billion budget on a so-called ``phase one'' defense that would, at best, be able to knock out less than half the soviet land-based nuclear missiles
that would still leave hundreds of land-based rockets to attack the united states, along with submarine-based missiles and soviet bombers
they haven't really come up with a successful technology yet,'' pike said. ``in fact, they've had a lot more success eliminating some things, such as the rail guns and the really exotic stuff.''
among the chief critics of star wars have been a succession of soviet leaders, particularly mikhail s. gorbachev, the current soviet leader
gorbachev has warned time and again that star wars is the major hurdle to a u.s.-soviet treaty eliminating half the thousands of atomic weapons each side has aimed at each other. but reagan has adamantly refused to agree to any limits on star wars research
gorbachev has also warned that the soviets are working on a system to counter sdi. at last december's summit meeting in washington, he said, ``if the americans have a lot of money, let them squander it on sdi. we will look for a response along other, asymmetrical lines that will be less expensive.''
u.s. officials no longer talk about the possibility of eliminating nuclear weapons. instead, they say sdi will make it more difficult for the soviets to be sure of knocking out american weapons in any attack, thus making it harder for the soviets to attack
defense secretary frank c. carlucci, in his annual report to congress, said, ``the deterrent value of strategic defenses derives from the effect these defenses would have on soviet calculations on the costs and benefits of launching an attack.''
this type of defense would enable us to influence the soviet decision-maker's calculus by diminishing his confidence in the ability of his forces to execute an effective attack, rather than by increasing the severity of our retaliation,'' he said. ``a strategic defense need not be `leak-proof' to achieve this objective.''
star wars also has been the subject of annual congressional fights over spending. the democratic-controlled congress has consistently reduced sdi spending
reagan took aim at congress last week, when he said capitol hill ``should realize it's no longer a question of whether there will be an sdi program or not _ the only question will be whether the soviets are the only ones who have strategic defenses while the united states remains entirely defenseless.''
while the debate goes on, so does the research, particularly on the so-called ``phase one'' system
the plan is based on a system of 200 to 400 orbiting satellites, each of which would have 10 so-called ``kinetic kill vehicles,'' or rockets, that would destroy a target by slamming into it at high speeds
the pentagon declines to estimate the cost of phase one, but the congressional research service recently said the bill could come to more than $200 billion
pike said one of the main obstacles to sdi eventually will be the budget. ``you've already seeing intense competition for defense department dollars and that will only increase in the future,'' he said
anti-apartheid activists pledged to defy authorities monday in the first nationwide protest since the government banned leading black opposition groups last month
pamphlets urging a general strike were circulating through black townships in defiance of government regulations. police have threatened action against strike organizers and promised to protect blacks wishing to work
organizers called for the one-day strike to commemorate the 28th anniversary of the sharpeville massacre and protest banning of the united democratic front and other groups
the front, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, coordinated previous nationwide protests during the 21-month-old state of emergency. emergency regulations outlaw calls for strikes and boycotts, but hundreds of thousands of black workers and students have joined past protests by staying away from jobs and schools
in soweto, one major protest meeting was held sunday at a roman catholic church. speakers from some of the organizations which have been restricted addressed a crowd of more than 1,500
police entered the church during the meeting to ask that the participants stop singing freedom songs, but the songs resumed after the officers left, according to people at the church
services were scheduled monday in several cities and townships to mark the anniversary of the 1960 massacre in sharpeville, a township south of johannesburg. sixty-nine blacks were killed and about 180 injured when police fired on thousands of demonstrators protesting pass laws, repealed in 1986. those laws restricted freedom of movement as part of the national apartheid system of racial segregation
several affiliates of the united democratic front that were unaffected by the ban took out newspaper advertisements announcing monday's protest
the depth and extent of our people's anger about the bannings has surprised even us,'' said a statement issued by the affiliates. ``not sated with the whole country under the state of emergency and hundreds filling the prison cells, the regime is turning to blocking all avenues of peaceful protest.''
the predominantly white university of cape town and mostly mixed-race university of the western cape were shutting down monday in solidarity with the protest. monday's performance of ``district six,'' a musical with an anti-apartheid theme playing to full houses in johannesburg, was also canceled
sharpeville made news again last week because friday had been set as execution date for six black prisoners, known as the ``sharpeville six.'' they were convicted of complicity in the mob killing of a black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots in 1984
president p.w. botha rejected worldwide appeals for clemency, but a supreme court judge granted a one-month stay of execution thursday to consider defense claims of lying by a key witness
president francois mitterrand on sunday promised to reveal this week whether he will seek re-election, a question that has kept the country in suspense for months
i hear you, believe me. it seems you want me to tell you today, today about tomorrow,'' mitterrand said in a videotaped message to a political rally of 20,000 socialists and presidential supporters in the paris suburb of bourget
political pundits predict mitterrand will announce his plans at a meeting of the socialist party in strasbourg on friday, just four weeks before voters go to the polls
guessing about the socialist president's plans has become something of a parlor game in france. sometimes the 71-year-old president has hinted he would like to retire, but on other occasions has left the impression he would seek another term
the magazine paris-match has sponsored a contest asking readers to guess whether mitterrand will run, the day of his decision, and the exact minute it will be announced. the winner will have income taxes paid by the magazine for the seven-year term of the next president
as the april 5 deadline nears for candidates to place their names on the ballot, it seems increasingly likely mitterrand will run
lionel jospin, first secretary of the socialist party, reinforced this impression in comments made to reporters before the president's speech
to win, it is necessary that a candidate have the stature of a president. we have it, or in any case in some days i am convinced we are going to have it _ with francois mitterrand,'' jospin said
polls have consistently placed mitterrand ahead of the two other leading contenders for the presidency, conservative premier jacques chirac and former premier raymond barre, the other main conservative candidate
in fact, the first round of the election april 24 is regarded as a sort of primary election between the rival conservatives. the winner would then face mitterrand _ if he runs _ in a decisive second round may 8
a poll published in the journal du dimanche newspaper sunday showed 55 percent of the 1,813 people polled were satisfied with mitterrand. forty-eight percent were satisfied with chirac as premier
a handful of minor-party contenders, including andre lejoinie of the once powerful communists, are expected to draw a total of 5 percent of the vote or less. jean-marie le pen of the extreme-right national front could get about 10 percent of the vote
francois cornut-gentille, a political expert with the independent sofres polling firm, said ``the right is divided between barre and chirac, so mitterrand is the unifier. he has the image of ... a man of state.''
the image has led to a groundswell of support for the president who has enjoyed enormous popularity, despite his national non-campaign. independent campaigns have sprung up around the country, gathering signatures and putting up posters for ``tonton,'' mitterrand's nickname, an affectionate term for uncle
chirac spokesman alain juppe said mitterrand's strategy has been to ``remain outside the melee and continue to act like the father of the country on his little pink cloud.''
some experts predict that when mitterrand enters the political fray his image may take a beating
carol pittas thought it was a little strange when a passing motorist asked if the lion on the hill was real. but after a few more passers-by asked the same question, pittas and her fellow rip van winkle bridge toll collectors thought twice
sure enough, a full-grown, 200-pound adult lioness was resting just 25 feet from the entrance to the upstate hudson river bridge friday night
it was just lying there and all these passing cars were asking about it,'' pittas said. ``one guy asked if he could keep it if he caught it.''
it seems the lioness was an escaped pet from a nearby river estate. the owners were on vacation and somehow the lioness broke free and found its way to the bridge approach, state trooper ron levin said
police were called to the scene along with two animal handlers from the nearby catskill game farm to sedate the animal with a tranquilizing gun
it wasn't too friendly,'' levin said. ``and it got really upset when it was shot.''
when hit by the dart, the lioness roared and ran into an adjacent wooded area and headed toward the river. police and the animal handlers followed
animal handler jurgen schultz used a flashlight to find the cat again and gave her another tranquilizing dart in the flank for insurance
after the tranquilizer took effect, six men took the lioness out of the woods on a stretcher and loaded her into a rescue van, levin said
the lioness was held at the catskill game farm until the feline's owner, martin kosich, picked it up late saturday afternoon
political wheels are turning in an effort to prevent the navy from bailing out of the famous nanaimo-to-vancouver bathtub race
the canadian armed forces has provided a communications network, boats and emergency personnel free of charge for the race ever since it was first run in 1967. but organizers at the loyal nanaimo bathtub society were told this year they would have to foot the bill if the navy takes part
the move has spurred a lobbying effort by nanaimo-alberni legislator ted schellenberg, who raised the issue in parliament last week
the citizens of nanaimo call on the department of national defense to once again take part in tubbing and to sail with those who bail,'' the progressive conservative member of parliament said
bathtub society commodore john ruttan said the pullout is a serious concern for organizers of the summer event. nanaimo mayor frank ney blamed the retreat on ``some bureaucratic paperslinger'' who interpreted department rules too closely
i'm quite sure that when the message gets to the right person, the navy will be allowed to return,'' said ney. ``they may even make someone walk the plank.''
the race with motorized tubs is about 20 miles long, from nanaimo on vancouver island to the mainland across georgia strait
a lightning bolt struck the minaret of a vacant mosque on sunday and sent it toppling onto the home of the building's caretaker, killing one woman and seriously wounding a child, police said
an eyewitness told israel army radio: ``at noon fire came out of the sky and struck the minaret of the mosque. at the top of the minaret was a crescent made of copper. the lightning hit the crescent and started a fire.''
police spokeswoman dalia gilad said the mosque, which was abandoned during the 1948 middle east war, was run down and badly battered during heavy winter rains. it sits in an exclusively jewish suburb of tel aviv
it was looked after by razi deib, an israeli arab whose home was inside the courtyard of the building
gilad said stone blocks fell on deib's house, killing his mother-in-law, naha takos, 70, and seriously wounding his 3-year-old son, ahmed deib. deib's wife suffered minor injuries. deib and two other children were not at home
the israeli news agency itim said the mosque hadn't been used for worship since 1948 but that moslems came to the site to celebrate family occasions and festivals
anglican bishops from throughout southern africa plan an emergency meeting this week to discuss the threat of government action against archbishop desmond tutu, the church said sunday
tutu, the first black to lead the anglican church in south africa, has been engaged in increasingly bitter confrontations with the white-led government since last month, when it banned political activity by leading black anti-apartheid groups
tutu, winner of the 1984 nobel peace prize for his fight against apartheid, was briefly detained three weeks ago when he and other church leaders tried to march to parliament with a petition protesting the crackdown on opposition activity
he and other clergymen, including the rev. allan boesak, subsequently vowed to continue challenging the government. boesak is president of the world alliance of reformed churches
south africa's anglican bishops, in a statement sunday, said the government has ``launched a carefully planned attack'' on tutu and boesak ``aimed at portraying them as marxists and isolating them from their churches as a prelude to state action against them.''
president p.w. botha met with tutu last week and suggested that the archbishop had aligned himself with the outlawed african national congress guerrilla movement
the bishops' meeting on tuesday is to take place at jan smuts airport outside johannesburg. the right rev. keith sutton, a bishop from litchfield, england, is to join african bishops at the meeting as the representative of the archbishop of canterbury, the right rev. robert runcie
watergate conspirator jeb stuart magruder says his past was the perfect prologue to his new post as the head of the city's commission on values and ethics, formed after scores of people scooped up cash that fell from an armored car
magruder, now a presbyterian minister, was a deputy director of communications in the nixon white house and spent seven months in jail for his role in the watergate scandal
magruder, 53, who calls watergate one of the greatest ethical scandals of modern times, said in an interview that what he learned from watergate qualifies him to lead the 15-member panel of business, education and religious leaders
watergate happened 15 years ago. since that period of time, i have spent most of my life in preparation for the ministry and in the ministry. and in doing that i took on as kind of my issue _ because of watergate i'm sure _ the issue of ethics. that automatically hit a responsive chord in me,'' he said, laughing
magruder was ordained a presbyterian minister in 1981 and since has divided his time between his duties at first community church and speaking to groups around the state about ethics. he is almost finished writing a book on the subject
i do have a fairly unique kind of a pattern to discuss ... being involved in one of the great scandals of our country, which was an ethical scandal,'' he said. ``and studying ethics from a theological viewpoint, i have come to some conclusions about what is happening in this life.''
those conclusions include a major change from his code of ethics in the watergate era
if they haven't changed, then it has been a real waste of time, hasn't it?'' he said
the commission's goal is to generate discussion of ethics and values by city residents. to that end, it is sponsoring a forum april 23 featuring sen. mark hatfield, r-ore., plans presentations in schools and eventually will distribute a questionnaire posing ethical questions that it hopes will spur consideration of the issues
it was the brainchild of mayor dana rinehart and others, including magruder, who have gathered monthly for informal lunch meetings since last fall. their talk turned to values and ethics in october after the rear door of an armored car flew open and bags of cash spilled onto interstate 71
an estimated 200 people converged on the freeway, some to gawk but most to scoop up flying bills
a telephone worker was given a mayoral proclamation and a reward for returning $57,000, but many others kept the money
how much cash was lost and how much was recovered has never been publicly released, but published figures estimate that as much as $1 million may have fallen from the truck
i wasn't surprised people didn't return the money,'' magruder said. ``but ... that same week, a poll came out that said something like 90 percent of the state wants honesty as its key factor in its elected officials, yet when people were polled about whether they would have taken the money on the freeway, 60-some percent of them said they would
when you have that kind of hypocrisy in the body politic, you're going to have confusion.''
rinehart said he wasn't surprised either, but began to think more about values and ethics when he talked to his three children about it
they didn't have a clear-cut answer. they said it probably didn't matter since the money was insured and then they said that nobody would know if they kept it,'' rinehart said. ``i couldn't believe it. i said, `you'd know
that's why we have the commission, to get a grip on where our values and ethics are and spark a little discussion, to get rid of this myopic view some of have of reality. i really don't think the rolex watch and bmw neighborhoods are fulfilling people anymore. people need more in their lives.''
the owner of a popular bar where a bomb blast injured 13 people, including five american servicemen, said sunday that he had never received threats or warnings of an attack
no extremist organization claimed responsibility for the blast at popular oscar's bar, and greek police said the saturday night attack did not fit the style of greek terrorist organizations
the blast smashed windows and collapsed the bar's wooden ceiling but caused no serious injuries. about 25 people _ greeks, britons and americans _ were drinking when the bomb went off
people round here know us as an american hangout but i never got any threatening calls,'' said the bar's owner, panayotis papoulias
the four americans injured suffered cuts and puncture wounds and were released after treatment from the hospital at hellenikon air force base, an american embassy official said
a statement issued by the base identified the americans as air force staff sgts. larry morrison, timothy johnson, ricky hoover and john fines, all serving at hellenikon. their ages and hometowns were not given
the statement said a fifth serviceman, staff sgt. michael grasta, had been examined by medics at the scene of the explosion
it was the first time i'd been to oscar's, and i was standing at the counter with my drink, there was a big noise and i saw the bar blow up in front of me,'' said costas pabalos, 25, a greek man who suffered first-degree burns
a police spokesman said fragments of a timing device were found among debris in the bar, indicating the bomb went off as planned at 11:10 p.m
oscar's is a well-known meeting place for americans in the seaside suburb of glyfada, close to the hellenikon base
more than 1,200 americans are stationed at the 7206 air base group at hellenikon, next to athens international airport
a spokesman at the asklipeion voula hospital where the injured were taken said two britons, identified as christine slater and john summers, 24, were released sunday
the spokesman said four greeks were still hospitalized
the explosion came two weeks after a greek left-wing terrorist organization, november 17, claimed responsibility for killing a leading greek businessman, but a senior police official said there was no indication the attacks were linked
this bombing doesn't follow the style of any known greek terrorist group,'' the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity
november 17 has claimed attacks against americans in the past, including bombings in april and august 1987 against buses carrying u.s. servicemen in athens. more than 30 americans were injured in the two attacks, one seriously
the group, which seeks immediate closure of american bases in greece, is named for the day in 1973 that troops crushed a student rebellion against the 1967-74 right-wing dictatorship
greece and the united states currently are negotiating a new agreement for the four american military bases in greece
the last bar bombing in athens took place in february 1985. more than 60 people, including 34 americans, were injured in an explosion at bobby's bar in glyfada
no extremist group claimed responsibility for that attack and no arrests were made. spelling to maher. picks up 19th graf, ``the panamazation ...'</note>
when strikes shut down the rest of the country, panama canal employees went to work. when flaming barricades blocked downtown streets, roads to the canal were clear. the crisis gripping the rest of the country has barely touched the waterway so vital to panama's economy
even at the height of this week's protests, rioters demanding the ouster of strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega avoided the canal zone just outside the capital
canal officials said the most serious problem was a transit stoppage that made it impossible for many canal employees to get to work
after last wednesday's failed coup attempt and street riots, the joint u.s.-panamanian commission that has governed the canal since 1979 issued a reassuring statement
we expect surface transit to continue without interruption,'' said the canal's marine director, george hull
but not everyone agrees
capt. john maher, president of the 230-member panama canal pilots association, said continued political instability could sound the waterway's death knell
ship builders are already planning for the year 2000, when panama takes full control of the waterway, he explained, and they must decide now whether new fleets will be small enough to fit through the 110-foot-wide lock chambers
the association pilots guide ships large and small through the canal, its locks and other installations
maher fears that if builders have doubts about the canal's future, they will opt to build larger ships. about 1,800 ships worldwide are already too big to pass through the locks
an average of 33 ships a day pass through the 50-mile set of locks and lakes. canal officials said 37 made the trip the day of the coup attempt and 39 passed through the next day, despite work stoppages at ports on both sides of the waterway
even the power outages that plagued the rest of the country did not affect the canal because the commission generates its own power
the canal, along with offshore banking, a thriving re-export industry and a large u.s. military presence, has made panama the most prosperous country in central america. canal revenues make up about 10 percent of panama's gross national product
in 1987, the canal made direct payments of $78.1 million to panama from toll revenue of just under $330 million. much of the rest of the revenue, which goes to maintenance, salaries and other expenditures, also helped swell the national economy
but years of deficit spending also piled up a $4.5 billion foriegn debt that led to civil unrest, capital flight and loss of government income. local banks have been closed for weeks because the government could not provide them with enough money to cover a run. panama has no currency of its own and uses the u.s. dollar
the united states has been applying economic pressure in hopes of forcing noriega to resign. it cut off military and economic aid and withheld $6.5 million in canal fees last week
the canal commission is sensitive about the problems the chaos is creating for what it insists is a ``non-political maritime waterway.'' commission spokeswoman mercedes morris said the rioting and unrest have unfairly frayed the waterway's reputation
maher finds the cloud over the canal particularly galling because of its smooth transition so far to direct panamanian control under a 1979 treaty with the united states
the panamazation of the canal has been a great success,'' he said.``and if the canal can come through the current problems unscathed, the future is great.''
the canal and the treaties returning it to panama evoke fervent nationalism
in 1979, the united states turned the canal zone over to panama, ending an era of american courts, postal services, police and even a company store
but about 10,000 american troops are still stationed in bases in panama, home of the u.s. southern command, the nerve center for all american military activity in latin america. the canal treaties say the u.s. bases will go at the end of the century
shopkeeper steve nicholson is offering a pay now, die later service _ a do-it-yourself casket
he says it can serve as a handy table or cocktail cabinet until needed for its true purpose
customers can buy a wooden casket kit in sections for assembling at home at prices from about $100. nicholson said he sold five in his first week, the observer weekly reported sunday
the idea was initially an alternative for people who could not afford expensive funerals,'' nicholson, 29, said at his shop in gainsborough, eastern england
customers will save a fortune as the price of coffins continues to go up. naturally i have reserved one for myself,'' he said. shultz' comments on contra aid proposal.</note>
national security adviser lt. gen. colin powell said sunday the fighting between nicaragua and honduras is basically over and the chance of involvement by u.s. troops in combat is unlikely
i don't expect that they (the u.s. troops) will get anywhere near the combat zone,'' powell said. ``the combat zone is rapidly disappearing as the sandinistas appear to withdraw, and i don't think there is any reasonable likelihood that they would be anywhere near the combat zone or getting themselves in a combat situation.''
the reagan administration dispatched 3,200 troops to honduras this week in response to the nicaraguan incursion across the border to destroy contra rebel camps and supplies. the u.s. troops were to participate in exercises far from the fighting
powell, who appeared on abc-tv's ``this week with david brinkley,'' said the exercises should be completed shortly and the troops will return to the united states
i would expect that in a short period of time the exercise will end and they will be on the way home,'' powell said
defense secretary frank c. carlucci had said friday that u.s. forces would remain in the region for 10 days and not take part in border fighting between the two central american nations
powell said sunday that based on ground fighting, ``the battle is pretty much over. the sandinistas have withdrawn. they're apparently on their side of the border again. they appear to be in a process of withdrawing or have withdrawn.''
and our troops are 50-60-100 miles away from the site of action, and no plans are being made to move them any closer,'' he said. ``i see no prospect of their entering into a combat situation.''
cease-fire talks between nicaragua's sandinista government and leaders of the contra forces were scheduled to resume monday in managua, but the possibility of negotiations seemed slim in light of the fighting
secretary of state george p. shultz, who appeared on nbc-tv's ``meet the press,'' said he was uncertain about the future of the peace talks
i think the likelihood is they will (resume), but i'm not certain of that,'' shultz said. ``there seems to be a certain amount of maneuvering among the parties, but i think a reasonable and sensible cease-fire would be a good thing. and so we're for it.''
shultz also said the administration is examining a bipartisan congressional plan of $48 million in new aid to the contras, including renewed authority for the cia to deliver previously stockpiled weapons
it's a very interesting plan. we're studying it,'' shultz said. ``(it) seems a little low on money, but it is an interesting effort on their part and deserves careful study, and i hope that something goes forward. it should go forward.''
powell denied published reports that the administration turned down honduran president jose azcona's request that u.s. helicopters be used to ferry honduran troops to the battle zone
the new york times, quoting an unidentified senior administration official, reported sunday that the united states rejected the honduran proposal, which was never made formally
we did not say no,'' powell said. ``we were in the process of examining that request. it had some funding problems and some policy problems. and before we had to answer definitely `yes' or `no' or even get a formal request, we found another way to exercise.''
he did not specify what type of exercise, but the times reported that u.s. officials were able to persuade honduras to accept a joint training exercise in which u.s. helicopters would carry honduran troops to about 30 miles from the nicaraguan border but 100 miles from the battle zone
we are not using u.s. airlift to move honduran troops to the scene of the action at the bocay,'' powell said, referring to the major battle site
powell denied that he had misled congress when he briefed legislators on wednesday and failed to mention that president reagan had decided, in principle, to send troops to honduras if azcona asked
we did not go into the specific options because we did not want it all over the newspapers,'' powell said
house majority whip tony coelho, d-calif., in an interview on cbs-tv's ``face the nation,'' contended the administration did mislead congress about plans to send u.s. troops to honduras
i think that what happened is that we were being briefed at 4:30 in the afternoon on day and they had made a decision that morning to go down. and they told us in that meeting that it was not even under consideration to send troops down to honduras,'' coelho said
i think that what is happening here is that we are being misled, or we were being misled,'' he added
gen. dwight d. eisenhower viewed his role in the 1944 invasion of france as the high point of his career, his son john eisenhower said as he helped launch the first navy ship named the normandy
former ambassador to belgium john eisenhower, the only surviving child of the world war ii military hero who went on to serve two terms in the white house, said saturday the invasion demonstrated the need then and now for a naval fleet capable of delivering forces anywhere in the world
a strong naval fleet keeps the american way of life viable,'' he told the 4,500 spectators who watched the 567-foot-long normandy, an aegis guided missile cruiser, slide down the ways at bath iron works' shipyard
i feel like i am representing my father, who regarded his role in the normandy invasion as a high point in a long career of service,'' eisenhower said, recalling how he accompanied his father to the beaches of normandy nine days after the allies' june 6, 1944, landing
the allied expeditionary force of 9,000 ships and landing craft, headed by the late general, carried 176,000 troops, 20,000 vehicles and 1,500 tanks across the english channel to reopen the western front against nazi germany
u.s. sen. george j. mitchell, d-maine, said the new ship's name ``is a reminder of the purpose for which she was constructed _ to protect american interests at sea.''
the normandy, the third aegis cruiser to be built at the maine shipyard, was sponsored by gayle wilson, wife of u.s. sen. pete wilson, r-calif. as mrs. wilson broke a bottle over the normandy's bow, scores of brightly colored balloons were released into the air
the ship, which will have a crew of 375, is expected to be completed in about 18 months, when it will be commissioned, said bath iron works spokesman jim mcgregor
a gunman opened fire at close range sunday on a reserve soldier standing guard near a palestinian refugee camp, marking the first israeli army fatality in four months of unrest in the occupied lands
the army's chief of staff, st. gen. dan shomron, said the shooting could augur greater use of guns by palestinian activists. he stopped short of saying it signaled a major change in the tactics of protesters, who have mainly hurled stones and bottles at israel's occupation forces
i don't think we can yet see this as a shift to an armed struggle,'' he said
but defense minister yitzhak rabin indicated stronger action would be taken to quell palestinian uprisings
to the extent that extremist palestinian terrorist elements try to combine terrorist acts with the civilian disturbances, we will have to adjust our operations and take harsher measures to cope with both,'' he said
the army identified the slain soldier as sgt. moshe katz, 28, from the northern port city of haifa
he was shot two or three times in the head at close range while guarding a government building facing the small beit jibrin palestinian refugee camp in this biblical city, the military said
troops immediately sealed off the road, the main tourist route from jerusalem to the city's manger square, the site of christ's birth. they also slapped a curfew on the refugee camp and ``rounded up everyone who was in the area'' for questioning, an army spokesman said
shortly after the killing, a dozen israeli soldiers guarded about 100 palestinians in front of shops. soldiers led them away in small groups for questioning
rabin and shomron rushed to the scene
it's a painful day, but we are determined to go on to make sure security will prevail in israel and the territories,'' rabin said later at the western wall in jerusalem's old city, the most sacred site in judaism
he told a group of supporters that the protests in the occupied territories had the same goal as the arab wars against israel: ``the purpose is through the use of force to get rid of us.''
bethlehem mayor elias freij said the situation in the territories ``will be aggravated'' by the shooting. but he blamed the frustration of arab protesters on israel's occupation of lands captured in the 1967 middle east war
the key to calming down the situation is in the hands of the (israeli) minister of defense and the government,'' he said
freij said that the army had used welding torches during the two previous days to seal 20 shops that were following hours mandated by the palestine liberation organization. he said souvenir shops on manger square had been shuttered for six days because of conflicting army and plo demands
in gaza city, troops closed the main vegetable market for three hours after firing tear gas to disperse arab youths who blocked a main street and hurled stones at troops, arab reporters said
israelis have been using economic pressure in addition to military force in trying to quell the unrest. they have cut international telephone lines and blocked fuel shipments
plo chief yasser arafat has said throughout the unrest that he ordered his followers to forgo use of guns against israeli forces. the army has reported only scattered cases of arabs shooting at soldiers or civilians
last thursday, an israeli civilian was shot in the legs near a refugee camp in the occupied gaza strip
israeli troops have killed 103 palestinians since dec. 8, according to united nations figures
the arab-run palestine press service said two more palestinians died sunday of wounds suffered in earlier clashes with soldiers, but these were not confirmed by the army
katz's killing took place a day before what underground leaders were billing as potentially the most severe confrontations yet. a recent communique circulated in the gaza strip and west bank called for major protests monday. they were aimed at marking the 1968 battle of karameh, when plo fighters helped repel an israeli force that attacked a guerrilla base in jordan
in other west bank violence, the army said israeli troops shot and killed a 26-year-old arab late saturday when their patrol was attacked with firebombs in the village of kfar dan, about 50 miles north of jerusalem. the arab-run palestine press service identified the victim as nameq milhem
israel radio said the death resulted from new orders calling for soldiers to shoot at arabs who throw firebombs
the ``midgetman'' atomic-tipped missile is a good idea that can do more to improve u.s. nuclear deterrence than putting mx nuclear missiles aboard trains, according to a house armed services study released sunday
the report by the democratic-controlled panel was the latest round in a long-running fight between the pentagon and congress over the best type of land-based nuclear weapons to build
the report was critical of air force plans to put mx weapons aboard trains for transport on the nation's railways during times of crisis
the air force is assuming that because mx would be roaming commercial rail lines only in times of international crisis, public resistance to launch-ready missiles in boxcars will evaporate,'' said rep. les aspin, d-wis., chairman of the panel
maybe that's true, but the air force has no evidence to support the assumption. on the other hand, rail-basing schemes have been shelved twice in the past because of public opposition,'' he said
but the air force was sharply critical of aspin
there he goes again,'' gen. larry welch, air force chief of staff, said, referring to previous aspin criticism of air force atomic weapons that the service says was unfounded
in a statement, the service said the rail-basing plan ``has been subjected to a rigorous, analytical, and careful acquisition process,'' and it said civilians would support the idea
the dispute has its roots in the bitter fights during president reagan's first term about whether the build the mx as a successor to the aging minuteman missiles, which are the heart of the u.s. land-based atomic deterrent force
reagan wanted 100 of the 10-warhead weapons, but congress cut the total to 50 because of fears that the large number of warheads on each missiles, combined with their placement in stationary silos, would make them easy targets for soviet attack
a presidential commission said the mx program should go ahead, but should eventually be succeeded by a single-warhead weapon, dubbed midgetman. aspin became one of the biggest champions of the midgetman and tentative plans were drawn up to build a force of 500 of the weapons and put them in western silos
but pentagon budget cuts in recent years have forced a revision of the plans to buy both the mx and midgetman, and air force and pentagon officials have made clear that their choice would be purchasing more mx weapons
in addition to the 50 mx weapons approved for land-based silos, the air force wants to build 50 more and put two on each of 25 trains
defense secretary frank c. carlucci told congress last month that he preferred to kill the midgetman program outright, but consented to including $200 million in next year's air force budget so it could be kept alive until a new administration makes a final decision
the house panel's study noted that a force of 500 midgetman weapons would cost an estimated $40 billion, but pointed out that the figure has decreased from the $57 billion estimate when the program was first proposed four years ago
by contrast, putting the mx aboard railroads would cost an estimated $13.8 billion, the study noted
aspin said that the midgetman cost figures, which would make it the most expensive weapons program in the pentagon, could be reduced as part of the effort to cut defense spending
giving each missile two warheads would cut the number of deployed missiles in half, or it may be that the job can be accomplished with fewer than 500 single-warhead missiles,'' aspin said
the report said the midgetman ``program appears to be operating under a sound acquisition strategy emphasizing risk reduction, competition and a realistic schedule at a time when some strategic programs are experiencing severe difficulties.''
but air force secretary edward aldridge, noting the higher cost estimates for the midgetman, said aspin's report took ``an extremely narrow view of what is in the best interests of our country'' because the money to pay for the more expensive weapon would have to be taken out of the budget for on-nuclear weapons
the net result would be a decrease in our conventional deterrence posture,'' aldridge said in a statement
   
workers unloaded tons of imported white florida sand from a barge in a developer's effort to turn a stretch of brown gulf coast beach into a sparkling bit of paradise
yes, it is white,'' said jay bottoms, a spokesman for the company unloading the 5,425 tons of sand saturday from the barge to the docks at galveston
the sand, amounting to a pile 200 feet long, 20 feet high and 60 feet wide, will be moved this week to the site of a multimillion-dollar resort development
later this spring, it will be spread over a three-acre area to be called palm beach, after the posh florida community
when completed, the resort it will accommodate about 3,000 people and include a 1,000-foot waterfront boardwalk, two freshwater lagoons complete with a 12-foot waterfall and white sand bottom. there will also be more than 100 palm trees, a jogging trail and a covered eating and concession area
