police said they were looking for three jamaican males, aged 16 to 23, who frequent parts of philadelphia and brooklyn, n.y
john garrett, 25, was denied bail in connection with the deaths of anthony williams, 13, and his brother, cornell, 15, and held on $1 million bail in connection with the abduction joseph jones, 12
the boys had been missing since last saturday. anthony williams was found tuesday alongside a railroad track with a bullet wound in his head and died wednesday afternoon, police said
garrett was arrested friday after jones told police he escaped from kidnappers near philadelphia international airport early friday. the boy said he and the williams brothers had been abducted by drug dealers march 12 and forced to sell crack, a derivative of cocaine
cornell williams was found dead near the airport friday with two bullet wounds in the head, the medical examiner's office said
iran's ayatollah ruhollah khomeini on sunday publicly ruled out any peace settlement of his country's 7{-year-old war with iraq
in a rare public appearance, khomeini said iran would press for ``final victory'' in the conflict. he said last week's iranian offensive in iraq's northeastern suleimaniyeh province constituted ``a slap on the face'' of iraqi president saddam hussein
khomeini urged his nation not to be ``deceived by foreign propaganda'' in an apparent complaint that the international media have ignored victories that iran claims on the war front
the 87-year-old patriarch of the iranian revolution made his comments in a nationwide speech broadcast by tehran television and monitored in nicosia, cyprus. he spoke in a strong voice and looked healthier than when he appeared on television earlier this year
his 15-minute speech marked nowruz, the start of the iranian new year
khomeini also urged moslems worldwide to rise up against the soviet union and the united states, describing them as ``forces of oppression and evil.''
the superpowers claim to advocate justice,'' he said. ``in fact, all they want is to impose their will and make us obey them.''
the national leader hailed ancient martyrs who sacrficed their lives preaching islam after the death of prophet mohammed in the 7th century
it is incumbent upon every moslem to rise up and sacrifice all he has for the cause of islam,'' he said
several thousand people marched to a u.s. naval facility sunday to call for dismantling of all spanish bases leased by the united states
protesters, mobilized by regional pacifist groups and the spanish communist party, marched nine miles from el puerto de santa maria to rota on spain's southern atlantic coast
they shouted slogans against nato and demanded an end to the jointly used naval base at rota as well as three u.s. air bases and nine communication centers throughout spain. when they arrived at rota, they formed a three-mile human chain outside the wall of the base
no violence was reported by police, who estimated the crowd at 7,000. organizers said 12,000 people took part
on jan. 15, the united states agreed to a spanish demand to withdraw the u.s. air force's 401st tactical fighter wing of 72 f-16 aircraft and an estimated 4,000 troops within three years from the base at torrejon. but the united states will keep use of its other facilities under a new eight-year treaty expected to be signed this spring
the socialist government of prime minister felipe gonzalez won a march 1986 referendum in which spaniards approved continued membership in nato, a military alliance joining western european nations to the united states. but the vote said the united states must reduce its 12,500 troops in spain
the warden of the federal detention center that was destroyed last november in an uprising by cuban prisoners is being promoted to a regional position in california
j.r. johnson became warden in september 1986, about five months after the center opened and about the time it was changed from a center for aliens awaiting trial or detention to a holding place for some of the cubans who arrived in the ``freedom flotilla'' boat lift but were deemed undesirable
he moves to san francisco on april 24 to become assistant director of the bureau of prisons' western division, overseeing the nine prisons in the western region
most of the center's buildings were burned in fiery riots that began nov. 21, after the 1,000 cubans there learned that fidel castro had agreed to accept up to 2,500 cubans who were convicted of crimes or were mentally ill. cubans at the federal penitentiary in atlanta also rioted
the oakdale inmates held 26 hostages for eight days before surrendering and being dispersed to prisons around the country. truck</head>
two men who helped retrieve some of the estimated $771,000 that accidentally fell from an armored truck nearly two weeks ago have been given plaques and rewards for their honesty
luis lopez, a television repairman, and daniel higginbotham, a postal worker, were also given certificates of recognition from the legislature at friday's ceremony
loomis armored inc. gave a check for $10,000 to higginbotham and $2,000 to lopez for their efforts in rescuing some of the money bags that fell off the truck march 8
three to five people who were driving or walking by when the truck dropped the loot in an industrial area scooped up plastic bags full of cash and sped off
a spokesman for loomis declined to reveal how much money was lost in the incident, but published reports have placed the figure at about $700,000
the opportunistic motorists or pedestrians could face felony charges of grand theft if they took $500 or more, police said. however, lt. barry johnson said friday that police have checked out quite a few leads but still have not found the culprits
lopez, 29, of daly city, was on his way home when the incident occurred. he picked up two bags containing $20,050 each and headed straight to a nearby loomis office
the following day, a unidentified woman gave police two plastic bags containing a total of $28,000
the money bags fell out of the truck in a crate. higginbotham moved the crate out of the street and waited for police to arrive. witnesses said he even grabbed bags of money from other people's hands and put them back in the crate
the armored truck, filled with more than $1.7 million collected from 20 banks in the san francisco bay area, was headed for oakland-based loomis' offices from downtown when the incident occurred
the driver, who was not identified, told police that the rear door was locked but that a dolly holding the crate slammed against it and forced it open
the driver did not realize the crate had fallen out until a honking motorist pointed it out several blocks away. by that time, a crowd had gathered around the bags of money
about $1 million in cash remained inside the loomis truck
an explosion sunday demolished two houses in the center of this port city, killing three people, including an 8-month-old baby, and injuring four others, police said. one woman was still missing
police said the 6 a.m. blast was apparently caused by a gas leak
the explosion killed a mother, her baby and one other woman who also lived in one of the houses
four people were slighty injured in the blast, which reduced the two four-story houses to rubble and damaged houses 300 feet away
police used specially trained dogs to look for more victims. they said there was little hope of recovering anyone alive from the debris
police said there were indications that workers had repaired the gas lines in the neighborhood during the week, and police were investigating whether this was linked to the blast
a newspaper reported sunday that druse militia members in lebanon considered trying to rescue anglican church envoy terry waite from his abductors but dropped the idea because they thought it lacked u.s. support
the sunday telegraph said waite is alive and being held by an iranian-backed radical group blamed for other kidnappings in lebanon
according to the newspaper, waite was involved in an accident that required surgery, but it did not give specifics
the newspaper said its story was based on an unnamed lebanese source who played a key role in investigating waite's disappearance in beirut in january 1987
the newspaper said in a dispatch from washington that waite, 48, is being held captive by a shiite group headed by imad mugniyeh, a member of the iranian-backed hezbollah, or party of god
hezbollah is believed to be the umbrella organization for groups blamed for many of the kidnappings of 22 foreigners held hostage in lebanon, including nine americans. the longest-held hostage is terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, who was captured march 16, 1985
waite, special envoy of archbishop of canterbury robert runcie, disappeared while on a mission to help win the release of hostages. no group has claimed to be holding him
the sunday telegraph said for three days after his disappearance, waite was kept in a house in the southern suburbs of beirut and was in frequent contact with the u.s. embassy in lebanon
it said waite was ``not really a hostage'' during this period, but was driven around the southern suburbs under escort to visit people in the area
the newspaper said waite was spotted by members of the druse militia who had served as his bodyguards. it quoted the source as saying they found the house in which waite was staying, tapped the telephone and monitored his calls to the embassy
it quoted the source as saying the druse considered a military rescue but ``did not feel they had the full backing of the americans for this.''
after three days of semi-captivity the negotiations broke down and mr. waite became a fully-fledged hostage,'' the newspaper said
leftist guerrillas exploded a powerful bomb at the peru headquarters of royal dutch shell oil company, wounding two people and starting a fire, police said sunday
the attack, the second in a month against the british-dutch firm, came a week after shell signed a preliminary contract to develop a rich natural gas deposit in peru's eastern jungle
a carpenter working inside the third-floor office and a woman selling candy and fruit on the sidewalk suffered serious cuts by flying glass when the bomb detonated shortly before midnight saturday, police said
the two were hospitalized and listed in stable condition
shell's main office is about four miles south of downtown lima
police blamed the attack on the tupac amaru revolutionary movement, a leftist guerrilla band that endorses a cuban-styled marxism. the group has been carrying out attacks in lima, mainly late-night bombings against targets it considers imperialistic, sice 1984
the blast gouged a large hole in the marble floor of shell's entryway, shattered windows and lights, demolished furniture and office equipment and sparked a small fire, which was put out quickly, police said
the explosive also knocked out windows and damaged doors of three banks and two other businesses in the building, according to police. 0164</first>
a small civilian airplane crashed sunday on quantico marine base as it was trying to fly out of a snowstorm, killing all three people on board, authorities said
nobody on the ground was injured, said federal aviation administration spokesman fred farrar
the single-engine cessna 210 left greensboro, n.c., at 8:25 a.m. and was headed for washington national airport, he said. shortly after 10 a.m., the pilot radioed an air traffic control center at leesburg for directions out of the storm, farrar said
the center was trying to provide that assistance when it lost radio and radar contact with the aircraft at an altitude of 5,000 feet,'' farrar said
marine base spokesman randy gaddo said the plane crashed in a field between a chapel where sunday morning services were in progress, and lejeune hall, the base headquarters
identities of the victims were being withheld until relatives could be notified
