drugs to relieve some of the devastating effects of alzheimer's disease are still years off, but there is at least a glimmer of hope for victims of the progressive brain disease, a scientist says
researchers from several nations met in springfield over the weekend at the first international symposium on the use of drugs in treating the disease
no one would have dared to hold a symposium until now, because there was no hope before,'' said dr. ezio giacobini, an organizer of the conference at southern illinois university school of medicine in springfield. he is a professor and the chairman of pharmacology at the school
the disease was first discovered in 1917, but there was not even a glimpse of progress until five years ago,'' he said in a telephone interview saturday
alzheimer's disease is an irreversible deterioration of the brain characterized by memory loss, with no known prevention or cure. an estimated 25 million people in the united states are afflicted
one of the encouraging aspects highlighted at the symposium, said giacobini, is that about a dozen drugs which may relieve symptoms are in various stages of testing around the world
for the first time we're looking at a number of compounds that do what has not been done before _ improve memory,'' he said
however, most of the drugs under investigation so far produce only minor modifications for short times
one drug that does seem to work is tetrahydroaminoacridine, or tha, but it has severe side effects, said dr. serge gauthier of the mcgill center for studies in aging, in montreal
it is being tested in the united states and dosage levels have been reduced to lessen liver damage, reseachers said. results are not yet known
experimental use of tha in canada has shown that while it improves memory as long as a patient takes it, about 80 percent of the subjects experience extreme nausea and vomiting, gauthier said
if we could find something similar but a little easier on the liver and stomach, that would be an improvement, but there's nothing better so far,'' he said
giacobini said chinese investigators at the symposium told of identifying two drugs _ huperzine a and huperzine b _ from a plant called huperzia and testing them on 500 victims of various diseases with memory-loss symptoms
they found that the drug increased the memory substantially,'' said giacobini. ``however the trials have only been done in china so far. they've never been replicated.''
the chinese drugs also have not yet been synthesized and must be painstakingly extracted from plants
tests of huperzine are planned outside china, in switzerland and in giacobini's laboratory at southern illinois
giacobini predicted that within five or 10 years some safe and effective drug should surface, ``not to cure but to help a lot.''
parliament on sunday approved a three-year extension of emergency laws passed in 1981 after the assassination of president anwar sadat by moslem fundamentalists
the government said the laws were needed to combat terrorist threats
the middle east news agency said the new extension would be in force from may 1, 1988 to may 31, 1991
the emergency measures are conducted within the framework of legality and sovereignity of the constitution and are under complete judicial supervision, and there is no reason to fear these measures which enable us to weed out plots,'' mena quoted a parliamentary committee's report as saying
the emergency laws ban demonstrations, unauthorized assembly and strikes, and give the government wide powers of search without warrant and detention of people regarded as security risks
they have been in existence since sadat's slaying on oct. 6, 1981. they were extended in april 1986 for two years
in asking for the extension of the emergency laws, prime minister atef sedki told parliament that the laws will be used in limited incidents and will not affect anyone with ``legitimate ideologies.''
interior minister zaki badr, who is in charge of police and internal security, told parliament that in the past two years, authorities had uncovered 227 cases of ``extremist action'' involving 1,458 defendants
he said these included cases such as the reconstruction of the jihad or holy war group. about 300 jihad members were tried after sadat's assassination and half of them were sentenced to varying prison terms for forming an illegal organization and attempting to overthrow the government
in addition, 20 members of the egypt's revolution group were charged with carrying out four anti-american and anti-israeli terrorist attacks between 1984 and 1987. no date has been set for the trial
badr said that police had seized large amounts of explosives, hand grenades, automatic rifles and other weapons with the various defendants
it does not take long to see the seriousness of the challenges and the amounts of dangers that surround us from every side,'' he said
i can honostely said that the emergency laws are a necessary measure that have no alternative. they will secure the society and protect it from serious dangers,'' badr said.  
a 35-year-old prison inmate who was barely literate when he began a life sentence in 1975 for the rape and stabbing death of a teen-age girl was honored sunday as one of seven outstanding adult learners
westville correctional center inmate ernest tope was selected for the award by the american association for adult and continuing education
i'm hoping that it will inspire more people in my situation to devote more time to education and vocational training so they themselves can achieve personal growth,'' said tope
he was the only prison inmate selected for the award. a 94-year-old california woman and a nicaraguan immigrant also were among those honored for overcoming great odds in pursuing their educations
since his imprisonment, tope has earned an associate's degree in general studies from ball state university and will complete an associate's degree in business in may from purdue university's north central campus, which operates the college programs at westville. he has a grade point average of 5.5 on a 6.0 scale and plans to earn a bachelor's degree
besides his achievements in education, tope has earned a reputation as a jailhouse lawyer. one case he worked on was argued before the u.s. supreme court
his publishing credits include an article in the journal of correctional education and an essay in a college textbook
prison education program director s. shannon reffett contends tope's greatest achievement is the impact he has on other inmates
a successful student out of the prison system is a far greater advocate than any of us,'' said reffett, who wrote tope's recommendation. ``someone like ernie, they can comprehend. his life is kind of a testament to what can be done in prison.''
tope said he had a criminal history at age 13, having spent time at the indiana boys school for joy riding and house burglaries. he said education had never been important to him, and he quit school at age 15 to work at a gasoline station
tope was convicted of murdering 19-year-old cheryl ann felger, who was abducted as she rode her bicycle near van wert, ohio, in april 1974
after he was sentenced, he was encouraged by another inmate at the indiana state prison to better himself and later took advantage of educational programs when he transferred to westville
tope's award was to be presented during a meeting of the indiana chapter of the adult and continuing education association, with a department of correction representative accepting it on his behalf
spring arrived sunday with a blast of snow and low temperatures in much of the northeast, while much of the west had balmy weather
by the time spring arrived here in pittsburgh, we had 2 inches of snow on the ground,'' said frank wells, a specialist with the national weather service
a cold front pushing across the northern and middle atlantic coast states was accompanied by snow showers scattered from the upper ohio valley through the central appalachians into southern and central new england
a small civilian airplane trying to fly out of a snowstorm crashed sunday on quantico marine base in virginia, killing all three people on board, authorities said. base spokesman randy gaddo said the plane crashed in a field between a chapel where sunday morning services were in progress and lejeune hall, the base headquarters
a thundershower with sleet and snow rumbled across nantucket, mass., during the morning, accompanied by wind gusting to 52 mph, and thunder also accompanied snow in new york city
four or more inches of snow fell overnight in northeastern ohio, with 8 inches reported at solon, ohio. up to 8.5 inches of snow was reported at sinclairville, n.y., with 3 to 5 inches elsewhere across western new york state and western pennsylvania and 7 inches in northwestern pennsylvania near lake erie
midday temperatures were only in the teens and 20s from central and eastern north dakota across the great lakes into northern new england
westerly to northwesterly wind blowing at 15 to 30 mph, with gusts to near 40 mph, was common from new york state and southern new england southward to the carolinas. the wind combined with the low temperatures to produce subzero wind chill values across interior sections of new york state
elsewhere, patchy light snow fell from eastern north dakota into upper michigan, while rain was scattered along the northern pacific coast
temperatures warmed to spring levels in the western half of the country with readings mostly in the 50s, 60s and 70s, and much of southern california and southern arizona got into the 80s
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 13 degrees at saranac lake, n.y., to 89 at palm springs, calif., and the miramar naval air station at san diego. the early-morning low for the day was 7 below zero at ironwood and marquette, mich
for monday, showers were forecast from the northern half of the pacific coast into western montana. a little rain or snow was forecast in minnesota and northern wisconsin, with snow flurries in northern maine and the lower great lakes
highs only in the teens were predicted for northern new england; in the 20s, 30s and 40s in the rest of the northeastern quarter of the nation; in the 70s in the central plains; in the 70s and 80s from the southern half of california to florida, georgia and tennessee; near 90 in parts of the desert southwest and southwestern texas; and in the 50s or 60s in most of the rest of the nation
the sandinista government on sunday protested attacks on sandinista targets by honduran forces and prepared for its first direct cease-fire talks with contra rebels
cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the mediator in previous talks and an observer to the monday discussions, expressed a hint of pessimism about their outcome
i see the situation as quite complicated,'' he said during his sunday homily. ``it is very difficult to reconcile two things that are completely opposite.''
the negotiations were scheduled for the southern border post of sapoa, 90 miles south of the capital near the costa rican border
the honduran bombings thursday and saturday along the isolated northern border were aimed at retaliating for an alleged sandinista troop incursion last week into honduras to chase contra rebels. there were no reported casualties in the air attacks
the nicaraguan troops are now in nicaraguan territory in the border area,'' deputy foreign minister victor hugo tinoco said at a news conference sunday, suggesting that the army had crossed the border. ``we can't retreat from the border area, because we can't abandon our right to defend our national territory.''
he denied reports that the sandinista troops remained inside honduran territory, calling them a lie by the reagan administration ``to obtain more money for the contras.''
the rebels have been fighting the government since nov. 1981 in a conflict that has killed more than 40,000 people. the cease-fire talks are included in a regional peace plan signed in august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, honduras and costa rica. the pact calls for amnesty, democratic reforms and an end to support for insurgencies
tinoco said monday's talks will center on finding a way for the rebels to lay down their arms. the government delegation will be headed by the nation's top military leader, gen. humberto ortega, brother of president daniel ortega
the contras say the talks should include political issues. their top delegate will be the rebels' leading political leader, adolfo calero
the sandinista newspaper barricada repeated its call sunday for nicaraguans to maintain a state of alert in the face of honduran bombs and american troops
the way the honduran government borrows yankee planes to provoke an incident could serve as a pretext for a direct invasion,'' the paper said in an editorial
vice president george bush held a strong lead among republican voters here, while massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson were ahead of other democrats in the wisconsin presidential primary race, according to a newspaper's public opinion poll published sunday
the milwaukee journal said it questioned 782 wisconsin resdents who said they were fairly certain to vote in the april 5 primary. the poll, conducted wednesday and thursday, asked the respondents which candidate they would choose in the open primary, which does not require voters to state party preference
among democrats, 38 percent chose dukakis and 30 percent supported jackson. missouri rep. richard gephardt had 11 percent; sen. paul simon of illinois also had 11 percent and tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 10 percent. the margin of error was 5 percentage points, the survey said
among republicans, 69 percent supported bush; 25 percent backed sen. bob dole and 6 percent chose pat robertson. the margin of error on the republican was 6 percentage points, the newspaper reported
with the new york presidential primary less than a month away, gov. mario cuomo indicated sunday that he has plans for a more active advisory role in the democratic presidential campaign
cuomo said he had asked his most trusted political adviser, son andrew cuomo, to begin consulting with all the democratic presidential candidates
up until a week ago, he was getting calls from everybody, but he told them all that he wasn't involved,'' said the governor. ``i have asked him in the last week or so to start taking calls from the candidates and help us by letting us know what he thinks of their campaigns in new york.''
the new york primary is april 19
cuomo's comments came on the eve of a meeting with tennessee sen. albert gore jr. but cuomo said he would give gore the same message he has given to all the other candidates _ that he he's not endorsing anyone yet
meanwhile, sunday's new york daily news reported that andrew cuomo might be on the verge of joining the gore camp
andrew is not leaning toward anybody,'' said his father when asked about that
gov. thomas kean scheduled a meeting monday with vice president george bush for the republican presidential nomination, prompting speculation that an endorsement could be in the offing
the meeting was arranged at the request of bush's campaign, said carl golden, a spokesman for kean. golden would not comment on whether kean would endorse bush
joseph ``bo'' sullivan, the chairman of a new jersey fund-raising group backing bush, said it was unlikely bush would meet with kean in the heat of the primary campaign unless the governor was prepared to back his presidential campaign
the time is ripe for everyone to make an endorsement. i don't see how anyone can beat bush at this point,'' sullivan said
kean has remained uncommitted to any of the candidates in the presidential primary
some of gov. bill clinton's enthusiasm for the super tuesday 20-state contest held on march 8 has apparently abated
instead of such a large-scale super tuesday, clinton suggested smaller seven- or eight-state primary elections, separated by enough time ``for candidates to really go into the states and get to know the people and the issues.''
a lot of the campaigning leading up to the march 8 voting, the governor said in his weekly radio address on saturday, consisted of airport news conferences and television advertising. thus, clinton said, well-funded candidates benefited unfairly
the governor said he had hoped super tuesday would give southern voters ``a more personal identification with the candidates.''
he said, though, that super tuesday accomplished some goals that had been his reasons for supporting the massive regional effort, including bringing candidates to the south and giving the region more influence in the nominating process. conventions</head>
jesse jackson has solidified his presidential bid in texas and should have about as many delegates as michael dukakis when democrats hold their state convention this spring in houston, the texas democratic party chairman said sunday
although dukakis earned more delegates in super tuesday's primary voting in texas, jackson appeared to have gathered more at-large delegates in saturday's 270 county and senatorial district conventions across the state
those conventions determine the allocation of 64 at-large delegates to the national convention, but statewide results of saturday's meetings were not tallied
with just over half of the 5,288 delegates accounted for, jackson had 41 percent and dukakis, governor of massachusetts, 36 percent. uncommitted delegates were running 10 percent; tennessee sen. al gore had 10 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt, 3 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon, 1 percent. former colorado sen. gary hart had one delegate, from a district in houston
i would just guess the state convention will be composed of one-third jackson, one-third dukakis and about a third of the people either gore, gephardt or uncommitted,'' said state democratic party chairman bob slagle
state democrats meet for their convention june 9-11 in houston, where they will chose delegates to the national convention
on saturday, republicans met in senatorial district and county conventions. many counties reported a record gop turnout at the meetings
although vice president george bush won all 111 national delegates to the convention, the gop battles were over delegates who will eventually write the party's platform and rules
a pat robertson-controlled convention in nueces county adjourned when their alloted time ran out and reconvened in a church a short time later. backers of bush tried to block the move to the church, but were voted down
that place was full of religious fanatics,'' said nueces county bush delegate steve cobb. ``they voted down everyone who voted against reconvening in a church out of concern for separation of church and state.''
among the democrats, supporters of dukakis and jackson wrestled in several areas. dukakis finished first in the march 8 primary, with jackson finishing second
in the 9th senatorial district of dallas, jackson carried the day by winning 153 delegates to only two for dukakis, while 104 remained uncommitted. jackson also scored an upset in travis county, which dukakis won in the primary. jackson took 138 delegates to dukakis' 99
texas democrats use a peculiar two-track system of picking delegates, with 119 chosen by state senatorial districts through the primary vote and the remaining 64 allocated statewide through a separate process of caucuses and conventions. overall, texas democrats were selecting 5,288 delegates for their june state convention, where the 64 at-large delegates to the national convention actually will be chosen
delegates to the state convention were picked from 63,380 people selected at precinct conventions held when the polls closed on super tuesday. saturday's conventions were held in each county, and in state senatorial districts in counties that have more than one state senator. the proportion for awarding of the 64 delegates was set at the more than 6,000 precinct conventions on march 8
the bureau of justice statistics will award grants totaling about $5 million to 20 states and the district of columbia to assist them in improving their crime reporting systems, the bureau said sunday
the federal aid, ranging from $18,000 for delaware to $373,000 for virginia, will enable the states and district to upgrade their crime information systems and make the information they submit to the fbi more accurate, the bureau said
under the new system, state and local law enforcement agencies will forward individual records to the fbi monthly for selected crimes and arrests rather than submitting monthly summary statistics, as they currently do
the bureau, which is part of the justice department, said the new system will enable police departments to describe the crimes in their area more accurately and could help them reduce the number of offenses
the new information that will be forwarded to the fbi will include the time and location of the crime, the victim-offender relationship, the presence or absence of a weapon and the number and types of offenses that occurred during each criminal incident
police departments and others reporting crimes will cross-reference arrests to the crimes that have been committed and distinguish between completed and attempted crimes. the definition of rape also will be broadened to include all forcible sexual offenses
alabama, arkansas, california, delaware, iowa, kentucky, maine, massachusetts, minnesota, montana, new york, north dakota, oklahoma, south carolina, wisconsin, virginia and the district of columbia have received their grants
four other states will be announced at a later date, the bureau said
the bureau announced the amount of the grants for only delaware and virginia
twenty-six states applied for the grants, although the bureau invited all 50 states to compete
production faltered in latin america last year after three years of growth, the interamerican development bank reported sunday
in the years 1984 to 1986, the official value of all production in latin america grew by an average of 3.8 percent a year, the bank said in its annual report. in 1987, the growth was only 2 percent. since population also grew at about that rate, the average income remained stagnant for the area as a whole
there was a wide range within the average
brazil is the biggest and most populous country and accounts for about a third of the area's total production. in 1986, its growth was more than 8 percent, and so was peru's. two of brazil's neighbors _ guyana, and trinidad and tobago _ saw declines in their production of more than 6 percent that year
the report does not furnish figures for individual countries in 1987, but says that none of the big four _ argentina, brazil, mexico and venezuela _ had a growth rate of more than 4 percent
however, about one-third of the 25 countries did achieve a growth rate of more than 4 percent, with the dominican republic and peru recording the largest increase, the bank said. the others in that group were chile, colombia, honduras, jamaica, paraguay and uruguay
meanwhile, incomes of people in about half the countries dropped again in 1987, the bank said, but did not provide any figure for that year. it put average income in 1986 at $2.145. the world bank estimated the u.s. average at $16,400 in 1985
lack of jobs and social security protection for the unemployed led to a big increase in latin america of what the report calls the ``informal sector,'' which refers to a huge portion of the economy never reported in the official statistics, ranging from bootblacking to heroin production
for example, the international monetary fund reported colombia's exports at $2.87 billion in 1986. according to estimates quoted by the manchester guardian weekly, colombia's medellin drug cartel grosses at least $7 billion a year
the report says that in 1986, only 10 out of 25 countries increased their production faster than the labor force and that preliminary figures showed a similar picture for 1987
this is a disquieting development,'' it adds
it explains that investment in new factories and equipment _ that is, the capacity to produce more goods _ must grow faster than the number of working people if more jobs are to be created. otherwise, the prospect is poor for reducing unemployment
with few exceptions, the high levels of unemployment and underemployment which have prevailed ... in the 1980s show no signs of diminishing,'' it says
it notes that over the past 20 or 30 years there has been:
_a massive shift of people to cities, out of farming and into industry and services;
_an ``explosive growth'' in the number of women working outside their homes;
_a significant improvement in the level of education;
_a slowdown in the overall growth of the labor force because of a declining birth rate
money flowed out of latin america for the fifth year in a row, reversing the historic trend: new investment usually brings a net inflow of cash to poor countries from richer ones. much of the outflow was in the form of interest payments and repayments on latin america's debt of more than $400 billion
the bank itself, owned by 44 govermnments, disbursed $1.919 billion in new loans to raise living standards in 1987, and got back $2.116 billion in repayments and interest. it authorized $2.361 billion in additional loans, down from $3.037 billion in 1986
efforts to increase its lending were stalled by refusal of borrowing governments to accept a change in the voting system on new loans. now, borrowers control the lending. the united states proposed shifting percentages needed to approve a loan so that it would have a veto over new loans whenever it could get canada to go along with it
chrysler corp. officials who met with business leaders to discuss the city's future after the automaker closes its plant here say they're being careful not to build false expectations
chrysler vice president robert perkins said saturday that company chairman lee a. iacocca cautioned him against making any promises about continued employment after the september shutdown
iacocca was censured earlier this year by state and union officials who accused chrysler of breaking a 1987 pledge to continue kenosha production for at least three years. chrysler denies making any written commitment
perkins led a delegation of 15 chrysler executives who met with state, city and county officials to discuss the company's plans to halt auto production in september, putting about 5,500 people out of work
perkins said iacocca told the company delegation before the meeting: ``don't repeat the mistake that chrysler management made, building up an expectation that we can't deliver.''
but the company ``is making a sincere effort'' to see if business can be sustained at the factory, perkins said
perkins also cautioned that government contracts sent to kenosha might not arrive soon enough to avoid the fall layoffs. it would take time to gear the factory to a new product line, he explained
in the defense business, there are long lead times. in the auto business, there are long lead times,'' perkins said
while pay for workers on the auto assembly line averages $27 an hour including benefits, the department of defense contracts held by chrysler pay $15 an hour or less, said rep. les aspin, who arranged saturday's meeting
aspin, chairman of the house armed services committee, was asked if he would use his influence in washington to get military work for kenosha
everyone who is in wisconsin doing defense work gets tender loving care from this congressman,'' he said
after saturday's meeting, an aspin aide said the congressman wanted another meeting with chrysler scheduled in the next month. perkins said, however, that no meeting had been scheduled yet, although follow-ups with individual companies would take place. elections</head>
chancellor helmut kohl's christian democratic union won a major election test sunday, retaining power in baden-wuerttemberg state but with a smaller margin
west germany's three other major parties also suffered percentage losses in the state balloting. two small right-wing parties scored surprising gains, apparently getting votes from dissatisfied farmers
three hours after the polls closed at 6 p.m., computer projections by the national television networks gave the christian democrats about 49 percent of the vote
they dropped under the 50-percent mark for the first time in 16 years, but the party will maintain its absolute control of the state legislature
its main opposition, the social democrats, had 32 percent, down from 32.4 percent in 1984
the environmentalist greens received 7.9 percent, just under the 8 percent four years ago, while the free democrats who had hoped to force the cdu into a coalition suffered a blow, getting 6 percent compared to 7.2 percent in 1984
two far-right parties acted as spoilers, but neither won enough votes to gain any seats in the legislature. the national democratic party of germany had about 2 percent and the republicans 1 percent
several smaller parties shared the remaining vote
according to baden-wuerttemberg's complicated election laws, the number of seats in the state parliament can vary, and the new legislature was expected to have 125 seats, one less than the previous one
led by lothar spaeth, the governor for 10 years, the christian democrats were expected to win at least 66 seats, compared to 68 in the previous legislature
social democrats had 42, a gain of one, and the greens also gained one for a total of 10
the free democrats lost a seat and will have seven
spaeth, 50, campaigned on baden-wuerttemberg's strong economic performance, and kohl said the results were a ``great personal victory'' for the governor
at 5 percent, the state has the lowest unemployment rate in the country, about four points under the national average
spaeth has transformed the southwestern state from a predominantly rural area into a major base for the growing electronics and high-technology industries
the result was a welcome relief for kohl's party, which had been slipping since the national election in january 1987
the christian democrats lost their majority in kohl's home state of rhineland-palatinate last may, and were forced into a coalition with the free democrats. the christian democrats and free democrats also are governing coalition partners in the federal government and in six of west germany's 11 states
kohl, speaking on national television, said the two small right-wing parties apparently picked up votes from farmers who are unhappy with spaeth's policies and want more aid
i don't see a radical trend,'' he said
a prosecutor says police officers misinterpreted an order to ``go on in'' when they broke down the front door of a house, drawing gunfire from an 84-year-old occupant who was then shot and killed by an officer
police converged on the home of dillard free last christmas eve after getting a tip that a rape suspect was hiding there
a grand jury on march 10 declined to indict the officer who shot free. a georgia bureau of investigation report on the incident remains sealed because of indictments against two people who directed police to the house and are accused of making false statements
but in an interview published sunday in the times of gainesville, district attorney andy fuller said he had decided to discuss the gbi's findings because ``the people of hall county need to know this information.''
fuller said the gbi found that six law officers who planned the approach on the free home remembered that detective robert gable directed them to use the normal procedure for serving an arrest warrant, that is, knock and announce: ``warrant.''
but officers lee west, gary lenderman and kirk williamson, who took up positions in front of the house, were not in the group given that instruction, fuller said
fuller gave this account of the subsequent walkie-talkie conversation: detective russell elrod told the officers: ``go on in.'' lendermen seemed surprised and asked: ``you want us to go?'' elrod answered: ``10-4,'' police parlance for ``yes.''
elrod meant for the officers to knock on the door, but the officers thought they were being told to enter the house, fuller said
west then knocked down the front door and he and williamson entered the darkened living room while sgt. benny patrick rushed onto the front porch, the district attorney said
fuller said patrick saw a silhouette moving inside and shouted ``police,'' but a shot was fired that narrowly missed his head. he said west, inside the living room, also shouted ``police'' and the figure fired again, this time striking a door frame
west then fired two shots, fatally wounding free
free's wife, agnes, 73, was hospitalized suffering from shock. she died march 5, three days after suffering a heart attack
the grand jury expressed outrage about the shooting despite its decision not to indict west, and called for a review of police procedures
the free family has hired a lawyer who said a lawsuit is likely
the rape suspect the officers were seeking was arrested on christmas day in texas
after three weeks tending to the dead and dying in india, former california gov. jerry brown says he has returned home with his mind on politics
after all,'' brown writes in the april issue of life magazine, ``that's what i spent a good part of my life doing.'' and while he never explicitly says so, he hints that he'll be returning to politics
after a six-year odyssey that took him to several continents and included an extended stay at a zen buddhist retreat in japan, the 48-year-old brown volunteered for duty earlier this year at mother teresa's clinic for the terminally ill in calcutta
he said his routine included bathing and hand-feeding men suffering from tuberculosis and malnutrition, changing and washing blankets and receptacles for phlegm, and holding the hands of the dying
to work with the dying and destitute _ getting a person a glass of water, helping with a bedpan _ is to encounter life at a very basic level,'' he wrote. ``people can be surprisingly happy and grateful when you help them with even the smallest things. ..
in calcutta i never escaped human suffering,'' he added. ``the most distressing thought of all was that much of this would be preventable or curable if nations could be mobilized to combat human suffering rather than to engage in national rivalries.''
brown, who sought the democratic presidential nomination in 1976 and 1980, said he returned to the united states on the day of the iowa caucuses and watched the coverage on television
as i watched, i wondered: `how could i ever take the spirit of mother teresa and apply it to the ordinary world of business and politics?'''
noting the emphasis this year on the personal character and private lives of politicians, he said: ``people are not just looking for a program or a list of ideas. they want virtue. they want a leader they can trust.''
a federal study has found no suggestion that drinking alcohol increases a woman's chance of breast cancer, a result that clashes with recent research
conclusive statements or general recommendations concering the relationship between alcohol consumption and breast cancer seem premature,'' said susan chu of the federal centers for disease control in atlanta
perhaps some alcohol-related factors, rather than alcohol itself, account for the effect shown by other test subjects, she said. ``we have difficulty explaining why our study differs from those other studies,'' she said
nobody has shown any biological reason why alcohol would raise a woman's breast cancer risk, she said
at a meeting of science writers sponsored by the american cancer society, chu described results of a study of 3,252 women between the ages of 20 and 54 with newly diagnosed breast cancer and 2,971 other women chosen for comparison
all the women were interviewed in their homes and asked about their alcohol-drinking habits in the previous five years. if they drank, they were asked to estimate how many days a week they drank and how much they consumed on each day
when data from the two groups were compared, chu said, ``we found no relationship between drinking in the past five years and breast cancer risk.''
two studies released in may that did find an increase in risk gained a lot of attention, she said
the studies, directed by scientists at the harvard school of public health and the national cancer institute, cited an apparent increase in risk with as few as three drinks a week
but the principal authors of both studies said the data were not strong enough to recommend changes in drinking habits for american women
the cancer society has no formal recommendation on alcohol and breast cancer
lawrence garfinkel, the society's vice president for epidemiology, said sunday that several studies had shown no added breast cancer risk from moderate drinking
the jury's still out,'' he said. if there is a risk, he said, ``it has to be very, very minimal.''
future studies should focus on the age that alcohol consumption began and how long it has lasted, chu said
in another paper presented at the science writers' conference, a researcher cited research data challenging the link others have found between dietary fat and cancer
calories are the dietary villain rather than fat, said david klurfeld of the wistar institute in philadelphia, who studied rats that were chemically treated to encourage tumor growth
the contention has been debated for some time among scientists, whose findings have been mixed
klurfeld said his studies showed the direct link to cancer risk appeared to be body mass, because the rats that exercised enough to work off calories had a lower cancer risk than animals that were sedentary
the cancer society says dietary fat may play a role in breast, colon and prostate cancers. it also says obese people run a higher risk of colon, breast and uterine cancers. klurfeld said he agreed with the second statement but not the first
he said his research was funded by the national institutes of health, the american institute for cancer research and several food companies that he did not name. the source of the funding did not affect results, he said
the cancer society's garfinkel said the fat-vs.-calories issue is an open question
i don't know how soon we can get it resolved'' because of the difficulty of studying it in human populations, he said. missile attack</head> pvs: in the persian... edits thereafter to trim</note>
iran claimed on sunday that iraq killed 5,000 iraqi kurds in poison gas attacks while trying to blunt an iranian offensive. it also said iran blasted iraq's two largest cities with 13 missiles
iraq reported its gunners fired a long-range missile into tehran, the iranian capital, late sunday. a military spokesman was quoted by the official iraqi news agency as saying such attacks would continue ``until the tehran rulers accept international calls for peace.''
there was no response from the iraqi government in baghdad on the iranian allegations about chemical weapons
but the iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the army's 2nd corps repulsed an overnight iranian assault in the central sector of the front, killing or wounding 1,200 soldiers
iran said it fired 13 missiles into the iraqi capital, baghdad, and the southern port city of basra on sunday in the continuing duel known as the ``war of the cities.'' it reported ``heavy casualties'' in its shelling of iraqi border cities
in the persian gulf, shipping sources said iranian gunboats attacked the 84,631-ton liberian-flag tanker atlantic peace with rocket-propelled grenades. no casualties were reported
it was the fourth iranian assault on neutral shipping in the past three days in the long tug-of-war for control of the persian gulf. iraqis made an air strike on iran's kharg island oil terminal saturday, leaving two tankers in flames
the iranians claimed they captured the kurdish towns of halabja, kholmar and dojaila in sulaimaniyeh province on thursday in the week-old offensive in the northeastern mountains of iraq
iran's official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, said the iraqis used cyanide, mustard and other unidentified nerve gases in the attacks ``to prevent the people from joining iranian combatants.'' many kurds, a semi-nomadic sunni moslem people, have been fighting the baghdad government for years
the agency quoted iranian foreign minister ali akbar velayati as telling u.n. secretary-general javier perez de cuellar that 5,000 kurdish civilians were among the dead
the iranian official reportedly criticized the united nations for failing to halt iraq's alleged use of chemical weapons. iran has warned it will begin using the same weapons in the 7{-year-old gulf war if iraq persists
the iraqi attack, if true, would be the struggle's worst with chemical weapons, outlawed under a 1925 agreement in geneva, switzerland. iraq denies it uses the weapons
the iranians said nearly 1,000 of the kurdish casualties had been airlifted to iranian hospitals for treatment. they appealed to the international red cross and other humanitarian agencies for medical aid
in the continuing exchange of missiles, the iranian news agency reported that, as iran celebrated the persian new year, its forces fired two long-range missiles into baghdad and 11 short-range rockets into the battered southern port city of basra
both sides have fired more than 200 missiles into each other's main cities and border towns since feb.29
the iranian news agency reported that at least six civilians were killed in iraqi missile attacks on tehran saturday night and in air raids on several of its western cities
a man who allegedly told police he killed his brother and three other people after they played a stereo too loud faces a indictment as early as next month, authorities said sunday
earl losier jr., 32, of bangor was being held without bail in the penobscot county jail after being charged with murder saturday and undergoing psychological testing at the augusta mental health institute
right now, he's charged with one count of murder, but i'm sure he'll be indicted on four counts of murder,'' said richard w. hall, the suspect's court-appointed attorney. hall said he expected the indictments to come in april or may
losier was arrested early saturday at his parents' house, downstairs from the apartment where the shootings occurred. he entered no plea during an appearance in district court
autopsies revealed the victims ``all died of gunshot wounds. at least a couple died of multiple gunshot wounds,'' said fernand larochelle, chief of the maine attorney general's criminal division
losier said he shot the four ``because he was taking cough syrup and because they were playing the stereo too loud,'' bangor police detective roy e. mckinney said in an affidavit filed in court that quoted a policeman sent to investigate the report of a shooting
police testified in court that a .45-caliber semi-automatic handgun was seized at the scene of the shooting, a dilapidated building containing several apartments about a block from the police station
bangor police lt. don o'halloran left word with a dispatcher sunday that no information about the investigation would be immediately forthcoming. police investigators continued to work at the scene
o'halloran said saturday that he believed losier is an unemployed laborer
police identified the victims as peter prendergast, 26, of brewer; his brother, michael prendergast, 31, of bangor; and sister, sharon prendergast, 23, of bangor; and stephen losier, 26, of bangor. ms. prendergast, described as stephen losier's girlfriend, was pregnant at the time of her death, officials said
jesse jackson, in an emotional, revival-style speech sunday punctuated by listeners' shrieks, told california democrats that ``there's room for you in the jackson campaign.''
the democratic presidential contender addressed some 1,200 delegates and guests at the state democrats' annual convention in affluent palm springs. he was the only democratic candidate to accept the state party's invitation to speak
jackson, arriving in the midst of a fractious party battle over primary election endorsements, called on democrats to unite and ``have hope when the jackson campaign comes to town.''
there was little that was new in jackson's 40-minute address, but delegates repeatedly stomped, cheered and applauded the candidate as jackson called for peace in the middle east, more jobs for american workers and help for farmers
jackson got his loudest response for denouncing the reagan administration's decision to send combat troops to honduras
we're sending troops to latin america, when we should be sending negotiators to latin america. our reasoning has collapsed in latin america,'' he said
the administration policy, he said, reflects ``desperation, a state of panic. we put military first, economics second. we're militarily strong, and diplomatically weak. we have guided missles and misguided leadership,'' he said
jackson called his presidential bid a no-frills effort
we're short on money, long on message and clear on mission,'' he said, ``if i can win against the odds i face, every american can win.''
he touted the fact that he leads in popular votes garnered in contests to date. massachusetts gov. michael dukakis leads in the delegate count, however
california's primary is june 7, and the state sends 336 delegates to the democratic national convention this summer in atlanta _ the largest state delegation
jackson said he has been successful at fund-raising, but he refused when asked afterward to detail how much money he has raised in california
we're doing incredibly well, and i can say that we will have every dollar we need to wage an effective campaign, a competitive campaign in california,'' said assembly speaker willie brown, jackson's national campaign chairman
brown has said jackson must raise and spend at least $1 million in california to win the state primary
peter kelly, the state democratic party chairman, said jackson's decision to appear at the convention ``definitely gives him a jump in california.'' says</head> catholic youths, reax from catholic minister; pickup 7th pvs, `the thought ...' subs last graf pvs, `protestant militants ...' to update with burial of protestant. edits to trim</note>
two british soldiers killed in a brutal attack by an angry mob had ignored orders to stay away from an irish republican army funeral procession, the british army said sunday
officials reported police fired plastic bullets sunday at youths who hijacked a bus in roman catholic west belfast. the shots were fired when the youths tried to attack a riot squad, police said
no injuries were reported
all soldiers in the british province had been told to stay away from saturday's funeral, an army spokesman said. he said an army investigation is under way
the two corporals should not have been where they were and we are interested in examining how that came about,'' said the spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity
they would have been briefed about the route of the funeral procession, and the two corporals were not expected to be there and had no requirement to be there.''
corporals derek wood, 24, and david howes, 23, who were wearing civilian clothes, were shot to death in belfast after people in the funeral procession dragged from their unmarked car, beat them unconscious and stripped them naked
the outlawed ira claimed responsibility for the deaths and the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, said it was questioning three people. police said they were studying videotapes of the attack
sinn fein, the ira's legal political wing, blamed the british government for the violence and praised those who beat the soldiers for their ``bravery in protecting the cortege from attack.''
there was a bomb scare sunday morning at a catholic church near the site where the soldiers were slain
although it was a hoax, the minister of st. agnes church, the rev. thomas toner, said at mass that ``the foul and bloody murders ... committed in our parish'' had put his congregation ``in the direct firing line'' of vengeance-seeking protestants
the thought of these two soldiers being savagely beaten and then shot in cold blood will give rise to feelings of revulsion in every irish man or woman who has a spark of human feeling,'' said cardinal tomas o fiaich, head of the catholic church in ireland
both soldiers belonged to the royal corps of signals, a regiment often engaged in secret monitoring of communications. wood joined the army in april 1980 and howes in august 1981
the army spokesman said the two had been traveling in civilian clothes between the belfast battalion's headquarters and near falls road and the british army's northern ireland headquarters
there are a number of possible routes available to them, but it is a matter of speculation how they came to be in a place they were not supposed to be in,'' he said
their restraint under the most hideous provocation was obvious to the entire nation,'' the statement said
the soldiers were killed when they encountered the procession following the coffin of kevin brady, an ira member and one of three people killed last wednesday at milltown catholic cemetery
in that attack, a gunman alleged to be a protestant extremist opened fire and hurled grenades at mourners during the burial of three ira guerrillas shot by british commandos in gibraltar on march 6. another 68 people were injured in the funeral attack
witnesses to the attack saturday said the soldiers' car was engulfed by angry mourners who apparently assumed they were undercover agents spying on the crowd
the army said the soldiers' weapons apparently were taken from them and used against them
witnesses said the soldiers were thrown into a taxi and driven to a nearby vacant lot where shots were heard and where their naked, bullet-riddled and battered bodies were found a short while later
prime minister margaret thatcher of britain and irish premier charles haughey condemned the violence
more than 2,630 people have died in 19 years of sectarian strife in northern ireland, where the ira is fighting to drive the british out. the mainly roman catholic guerrilla group wants to unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic
gillian johnston, a 21-year-old protestant killed by ira guerrillas, was buried in county fermanagh sunday. the ira said she was killed by mistake friday night and that the shots were aimed at her brother who it claimed works for the security forces. the family denied that
children found playing with the lid to a radioactive device missing from the trunk of a stolen car were not exposed to radioactive elements in the gadget, officials said sunday
however, because the lid had been removed from the device, officials said, there was a greater possibility for release of radioactivity
as of sunday, authorities were stymied in their search for the device, which measures the density of moisture in soil and contains the radioactive elements cesium 137 and americium 241, said larry krieger, a spokesman for the newark fire department
both substances are considered extremely dangerous
a much larger amount of cesium 137 killed four people and injured 121 in goiania, brazil, last year when a lead canister from a medical device was broken open at a junkyard and the glowing powder wase passed around
but the amount of cesium in the missing device was only a fraction of the 17 grams of the substance involved in the brazil disaster, officials said
the device contains only 0.1 milligram of cesium and about 15 milligrams of americium, said karl abraham, a spokesman for the philadelphia office of the federal nuclear regulatory commission. a milligram is one one-thousandth of a gram, so the amount of cesium involved in brazil was 170,000 times as much as is contained in the missing new jersey device
the gauge's lid was recovered saturday after police received an anonymous tip that the device was in a vacant lot where stolen cars are routinely abandoned, krieger said
authorities didn't find the device there, but they did find about four or five youngsters playing with the lid, he said
the children gave conflicting stories about how they got the lid, krieger said. they tested negative for exposure to radioactivity, he said
the gauge can be carried safely, but the nrc warned that ``any attempt to extract the gauge from the case could result in serious radiation exposure to anyone tampering with it.''
on thursday, authorities arrested four youths on charges of possessing the auto, stolen march 10 while its owner, a soil engineer, attended classes at the new jersey institute of technology
the bright yellow plastic box containing the device and labeled ``radioactive'' was missing from the trunk of the car when essex county police recovered the vehicle tuesday in the christopher columbus housing project
three hundred and sixty eggs did a delicate balancing act early sunday morning in a symbolic ritual attended by about 200 celebrators welcoming spring
considering the hour, more people showed up than i expected,'' said donna henes, the performance artist who helped organize the event
the egg balancing took place on a long table-like platform set up at the south street seaport in lower manhattan at 4:39 a.m., the precise moment of the vernal equinox, one of two points in the year when the sun crosses the equator and day and night are equal
according to henes, balancing an egg on its end is an ancient chinese custom that brings good luck to the successful balancer
scientists are dubious whether eggs really do balance during the equinox because of changes in the gravitational pull, but henes is convinced
its funny, because i've asked a lot of scientists about it and they say its impossible,'' henes said. ``however, when i ask them to join in the ritual and they see it happen, they become instant believers.''
henes, who has been observing the egg-balancing ritual for the past 13 years, said eggs are ancient symbols of fertility and spring around the world. ``easter is only one of many spring holidays where the egg is used as a symbol of rebirth,'' she said
participants began arriving at about 3:45 a.m., and after balancing their eggs they enjoyed them at a breakfast prepared by a chef from one of the seaport tourist attraction's restaurants, according to betsy jordan hand, a spokeswoman for the seaport. in israel</head>
american jews must take a more active role in israeli affairs if they hope to affect the country's policies in the occupied territories, a former aide to president jimmy carter told the american jewish congress on sunday
the congress, which will consider resolutions calling for israel to withdraw from the riot-torn west bank and gaza strip, opened its biennial convention sunday with a keynote address by stuart e. eizenstat, former adviser to carter for domestic policy
if we are only sideline kibitzers who throw darts at israeli policy from long range and then retreat to our comfortable everyday pursuits, we will not deserve to participate in the political discussions in israel,'' eizenstat said
eizenstat told about 200 conventioneers that american jews must end the ``passive, check-writing mentality'' and become much more involved in the political, religious and economic spheres of israeli life
it is also our future they are debating,'' he said
he urged his fellow american jews to make investments in israel and to spend time in israel to understand the country's perspective. however, he said, they should keep their comments balanced to avoid the ``volatile domestic political cauldron.''
the american jewish community ``should be full participants in the broad debate about the direction israel takes on political questions, such as the future of the territories, but it should carry on this debate, to the extent possible, in israel rather than the united states,'' he said
the discussions that do occur in the united states should take place in private, he said
public criticism will be used by israel's enemies to ``drive a wedge between american jewry and israel,'' he said
the convention, which will attract 400 to 500 delegates, also will consider the peace plan proposed by secretary of state george p. shultz in the face of arab rioting in the territories
shultz's plan envisions that talks on self-rule would begin may 1 between jordan, israel, palestinians and any other arabs wishing to take part, under the auspices of the united states, the soviet union, china, england and france. the plan also calls for talks to start dec. 1 about the future of the west bank and gaza strip that israel captured from the arabs in the 1967 mideast war
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir, who concluded talks with president reagan last week, has said he was outraged by the united states' suggestions of a withdrawal from the occupied territories
shamir has rejected another u.s. proposal, for a full-scale mideast conference, saying such a meeting would give the soviet union and its arab allies too much influence and might force israel to withdraw from the territories
a bird that apparently was blown 1,000 miles off course was flown back to its place in the sun with full vip treatment aboard a jetliner sunday
the alpine swift was cared for at a bird reserve until british airways offered to fly it back to faro, portugal
it was placed in a special box and given a seat on the birmingham-faro flight, the airline said
it has to be released carefully back into the wild,'' said a spokesman. ``it will be placed on the ground by a brick wall so it can climb up and get its bearings'' in its home territory
a new mexico high school student was selected sunday as the nation's top student leader, winsning a $10,000 college scholarship in the 1988 century iii leaders program
tony ortiz, a senior at goddard high school in roswell, n.m., was chosen from among 102 student leaders who gathered thursday through sunday to discuss national issues, said spokeswoman tracy curtin
being with these young people and participating in the century iii leaders program is enough to give an older person like myself a lift about the future,'' said former chief justice warren burger, who delivered the conference's keynote address
the program _ administered by the national association of secondary school principals _ included two students from each of the 50 states and the district of columbia
in addition to ortiz, nine runners up each will receive $500 scholarships
those nine included erik bliss of santee, calif., who attends helix high school in la mesa, calif; brad hammock of morgantown high school in morgantown, w.va.; susan hassan of grand blanc, mich., who attends goodrich high school in goodrich, mich.; donald kennedy of clinton high school in clinton, miss., and anna muzzy of blanchester high school in blanchester, ohio
the other runners up were christopher roblyer of edison high school in tulsa, okla.; brad sears of grain valley, mo., who attends blue springs high school in blue springs, mo.; danny siciliano of shadow mountain high school in phoenix, ariz., and kimberly west of enloe high school in raleigh, n.c
the program is supported by the shell oil company foundation. pvs, at the</note>
sen. bob dole, kicking off a wisconsin campaign swing sunday, flipped two coins into a wishing well, thinking perhaps of a badly needed win in wisconsin's april 5 primary
as he strolled around a sports exposition at the city's convention center, dole was asked by reporters about a milwaukee journal poll suggesting vice president george bush led him by a margin of nearly 3-1 among wisconsin voters considered likely to vote in the republican primary
there are no secrets,'' he said
i've got a lot of hill to climb before april 5,'' he said later in an interview
i met a lot of friendly people out there. it's tough when you're losing. it's a lot more fun when you're winning,'' he said
but i still have a lot of supporters out there. and we want them to know bob dole is a fighter, that we're going to stay in this race.''
the kansas senator said, however, that he would have to reassess his standing if he lost in wisconsin
we shouldn't be into this game about are you going to run or are you going to drop out,'' he said
but he added that after wisconsin, he would have to do some thinking about whether to stay in the race
we've been hearing the end is near, but people forget george bush stayed in eight weeks after he began losing to ronald reagan,'' dole said. ``eight weeks was enough for him to lose. but i think eight weeks would be enough time for me to turn some things around.''
at the sports exposition, he was presented with a fishing rod and fisermen's vest, and viewed a tank that served as an artifical fishing pond containing trout. a demonstrator cast a few lines but came up empty
dole was also visiting a veterans administration hospital on sunday. on monday, he was attending a farm day in northwestern wisconsin, visiting a vocational school in eau claire and touring a brewery in la crosse
dole's state campaign chairman michael grebe said he expected the senator's visit to be ``the kickoff to a strong effort in wisconsin.''
we expect to have a direct mail effort, radio and television advertising and continuing volunteer effort and volunteer phone banks,'' grebe said
dole was trounced by bush on super tuesday, and lost again last week in illinois. he has indicated he intends to remain in the race at least through the wisconsin primary
the milwaukee journal poll of 732 wisconsin residents showed 69 percent of those planning to vote republican preferred bush, 25 percent chose dole and 6 percent chose pat robertson. rioting</head>
a government commission announced it will begin an investigation monday into the death of a university student that sparked riots in the burmese capital
guards protected government buildings in rangoon over the weekend, following protests friday in which demonstrators wrecked cars, set fire to a department store and chanted anti-government slogans
some rangoon residents said there were casualties and mass arrests by security forces, but the government-controlled news media was virtually silent on the disturbances
open protests have been rare in burma since president ne win seized power in 1962 and instituted one-party rule
but over the past two years, small demonstrations and outbursts of violence have occurred in reaction to worsening economic conditions
last september, hundreds of students in rangoon rioted to protest a government decision to invalidate three denominations of banknotes
friday's demonstrations began in support of students at the rangoon institute of technology, who had rioted march 12
one student, maung phone maw, 23, was shot march 12 and the government panel was set up to investigate his death
the rioting began after students clashed with local residents over whether to play a cassette tape in a tea shop, and police then moved in firing tear gas and making arrests. mission</head> palestine,' to reflect that korten now saying justice department might not file monday, but would file within the next two days if the plo doesn't close the mission</note>
the justice department is planning to file suit in federal court in new york to force the closing of the plo observer mission at the united nations, a department spokesman said sunday
we're ready to go ahead and file the papers if they don't close the mission voluntarily,'' said spokesman patrick korten
the palestine liberation organization served notice last week that it planned to defy any u.s. effort to shut the mission, which is in a new york city townhouse
sunday afternoon, korten indicated that the department would file suit monday, but sunday evening he said that such action might not occur until tuesday or wednesday due to possible delays in paperwork
the chances are it would be within a day or two if they are not out,'' korten said. ``we are hoping those who walk into the office (monday) to look for them would find them gone. if that's not the case, then we would proceed with legal action.''
the justice department announced march 11 that it planned to enforce the anti-terrorism act of 1987 by going to court to close the mission. that act takes effect monday
korten said the department planned to seek a court order directing the plo to vacate its offices in new york and said he expected the court order to be ``immediately enforceable.''
last year, the state department closed down the only other plo office in the united states, an information office in washington, in what was a futile attempt to head off legislation ordering the u.n. mission closed
the united states and israel consider the plo a terrorist organization, but the united nations recognizes it as the only legitimate representative for the palestinians
a truck taking 71 pilgrims to a roman catholic shrine on sunday crashed through a highway guardrail and tumbled 300 feet down a cliff, killing 65 people, police reported
they said the driver was among those killed and the seven other people aboard the truck were seriously injured
the accident occurred as the packed truck approached the town of cachoeira, 1,170 miles northeast of rio, according to police chief jose braga who was contacted by telephone by the associated press
he said the truck had left nearby coracao de maria to go to the ``miracle grotto'' in sao felix, 100 miles away
we don't know what happened yet, but it seems the bus lost its brakes as it sped down the wooded mountain road, crashed through the guardrail and plunged down the cliff,'' braga said. ``the driver was found dead clutching the handbrake.''
he said the driver and 60 pilgrims were dead at the scene and four died en route to a hospital
among the dead were 20 children, according to rio's jornal do brasil radio station
braga said police and rescue crews from six towns in the remote region of northeastern bahia state went to the scene
truck loads of peasant families regularly make trips to the colonial city, built in the 1700s, and the grotto to seek favors of st. barbara, the region's patron saint, braga said
gold dropped 23 cents an ounce monday, opening at $447.67. it closed saturday at $447.90
