the great u.s. airline giveaway seems to be grinding to a halt
worried about the potential financial impact of burgeoning frequent-flier programs and triple-mileage travel awards, many major air carriers have imposed restrictions on the plans or are thinking of doing so
the frequent-flier plans, which reward passengers with free tickets or upgrades to first class after they have flown a set number of miles, were launched in 1981 to stimulate ``brand loyalty'' to airlines in a fiercely competitive climate
the giveaway escalated to fever pitch at the beginning of this year, when delta air lines introduced a new program to automatically triple the mileage accumulated by frequent fliers. most big airlines quickly followed suit
but the u.s. airline industry is facing a staggering revenue loss if the estimated 8 million people enrolled in those programs start redeeming their bonuses and bumping paying passengers. the accumulated value of those bonuses is around $1.24 billion, reckons julius maldutis, senior airline analyst for the investment firm salomon brothers inc
that compares with total industry revenue of around $46.7 billion in 1985, $50.5 billion in 1986 and just over $60 billion last year
the frequent-flier programs have really gotten out of control,'' said dan sheehy, a spokesman for united airlines. ``we're concerned with the direction that the programs are taking.''
john zeeman, united's executive vice president for marketing and planning, said in a speech early this month that the airline is considering imposing restrictions on its frequent-flier programs. he said the options under review include requiring that travel awards be redeemed by a certain deadline, and even eliminating free trips and providing only first-class upgrades instead
if united decides to limit its program, the changes would be announced in early may, zeeman said
many other airlines have recently slapped restrictions on their programs _ most notably by limiting the number of free tickets for any one flight. but the limits being mulled by united, a subsidiary of allegis corp. and the nation's largest airline, are more far-reaching and could be matched by the other carriers
the last thing these airlines need is more damage on their balance sheets,'' said peter tanous, an editor of frequent, a monthly newsletter on frequent-flier programs published in colorado springs, colo. ``the airlines are scared stiff that they may be forced to take a hit against their earnings.''
observers warn that the internal revenue service could decide to tax the programs, sparking a ``mad rush'' by passengers to redeem their travel bonuses. the irs indicated recently that it considers travel awards a form of reportable income when transportation costs for a frequent business flier are paid by an employer
and the financial accounting standards board is expected to require airlines to provide for the liability of unredeemed awards in their 1988 financial statements
the looming crisis has taken hold during an already turbulent period for the nation's airline industry. the business is coming off one of its worst safety performances in 1987, struggling with unions and threatened strikes against some big carriers, and worrying about the possibility of a recession later in the year
for now, though, many airlines are enjoying robust passenger traffic and earnings _ prompting them to raise fares recently and to eliminate some discount fares
analysts say nearly all the major airlines except delta have started to limit their frequent-flier largesse by instituting ``capacity control,'' or reducing the number of freebies on a flight
everyone else is doing it; you have to control and manage your inventory,'' said bob gibbons, a spokesman for northwest airlines _ which will start capacity control on april 1 for bonuses issued after feb. 15
even holdout delta has ``blackout'' dates, or certain peak travel periods when free tickets cannot be used. delta, the third largest airline, also has the unique requirement that frequent fliers must charge their tickets on an american express card
we want to remain competitive with the industry,'' delta spokesman jim lundy said when asked what might happen if united instituted major restrictions
some airlines also are looking at other approaches, such as replacing free travel with merchandise awards or hotel and car rental premiums
while they could significantly restrict their frequent-flier programs, the airlines are not about to eliminate them or triple-mileage awards altogether, observers say. when the triple-mileage plans were launched at the start of the year, the carriers assured passengers that the popular gimmicks would be retained through 1988
we recognize that there certainly is an economic impact associated with the triple-mileage program,'' said frank dinuzzo, managing director of sales promotion for american airlines. but, he added, american has no intention of canceling its program
indeed, some observers suggest the airlines may be caught in a sort of ``catch-22'' by their frequent-flier programs, forced to keep them because there is no way to end them
i suspect that if the airlines had their druthers, they would throw frequent-flier programs into a bonfire because they've just become so expensive,'' said michael j. friedman, a vice president of sh&amp;e inc., an aviation consulting firm
however, he noted, it would be extremely difficult for a carrier to end its frequent-flier program without all its competitors doing the same
u.s. businesses might have to pay billions of dollars in additional state taxes if the u.s. supreme court upholds louisiana's taxation of a new orleans store for catalogs that it produced and mailed from other states, attorneys say
the case involves a disputed $43,937.03 tax assessment against the d.h. holmes co. department store chain, but lawyers for both sides agree the monetary ramifications go far beyond that
i threw out the figure of $800 million at a meeting of the tax executive institute in new york. ... people said that was a half or a quarter of the taxes it would raise,'' william f. grace jr., an attorney for holmes, said in a recent interview
the case to be heard tuesday by the supreme court could be the most significant interstate commerce decision since the l.l. bean sales tax case in 1973, say grace and william pugh, a private attorney representing the state of louisiana
in the bean case, the court ruled that mail-order companies don't have to collect sales taxes from customers in states where they have no employees or property
use taxes such as louisiana's are imposed on property brought in from another state for use, consumption, distribution or storage. louisiana's use tax, as in most states, equals the state sales tax minus any sales taxes charged to the purchaser
the catalogs in question were designed in new york, printed in three other states and mailed from those states to customers with holmes charge accounts
we contend ... that holmes did not use these catalogs in louisiana. there was no use by holmes because when the taxes were imposed, the catalogs were being transmitted in the u.s. mails,'' grace said. ``at that time, they were not subject to tax. they can only be taxed when they came into use in the state of louisiana.''
if the high court upholds state court rulings against holmes, grace said, states could tax such things as flyers sent with credit card bills, catalogs from national chains with stores in their states, and telephone directories
all of the states are starved for revenues. they're going to look wherever they can ...it could turn into big bucks,'' said lee williams of the washington-based american retail federation, which filed one of seven friend-of-the-court briefs in the case
we think it would be a tremendous burden on business and could be crippling to ... retailers who send tons of their advertising and catalog materials across state lines,'' said williams, the ara legislative counsel
pugh said the case hinges on ownership
i would contend and did contend and shall contend that holmes owned the catalogs when they were designed, holmes owned the catalogs when they were printed, holmes owned the catalogs when they were mailed, and holmes owned the catalogs when they arrived at the post office boxes,'' he said
that kind of wording could mean big trouble for catalog companies, said bob levering, legislative counsel for the direct marketing association in washington, d.c
if the supreme court agrees that a company possesses and is using something while it is being sent through the mail, levering said, it could bring taxes on all kinds of mailings
they (states) could say ... your property is in our state, therefore we're providing police and fire protection for your property,'' he said
courts in tennessee, illinois, new york, ohio, south dakota, wisconsin and the district of columbia have ruled the opposite of the louisiana courts in such matters, said andrew rinker jr., another lawyer for holmes
since the louisiana decision, missouri has gone against us, based on the louisiana holding,'' he said
big guns have lined up on both sides of the argument
one of two legal briefs supporting louisiana was filed on behalf of the national governors association, national association of counties, council of state governments, international city management association, national conference of state legislatures, national league of cities and u.s. conference of mayors. the other was from the multistate tax commission
in addition to the retail federation, the direct marketing association, the national association of catalog showroom merchandisers and the committee of state taxation of the council of state chambers of commerce have filed individual friend-of-the-court briefs. magazine publishers of america inc., printing industries of america and r.r. donnelly &amp; sons co., a catalog publisher, joined forces for another
trade ministers from 27 countries ended three days of informal talks sunday without an agreement on agriculture policy, but issues a pledge to strengthen the 95-nation general agreement on tariffs and trade
the deadlock on agriculture is seen as a crucial issue in current world trade talks, which are scheduled to last four years
there was no movement of positions at all,'' australian trade minister michael duffy said after the meeting, which included trade ministers from the united states, japan and the european economic community
the united states insists that all agricultural subsidies be abolished worldwide by the year 2000. the eec maintains it will join in substantial cuts in agricultural subsidies, but rejects the long-term u.s. proposal
the third big party to the agriculture policy debate is the 13-country cairns group, the non-aligned, free-trade-oriented group of agricultural exporters. the cairns group is calling for short-term measures to freeze subsidies and for long-term reform in farm policy
duffy said he outlined the cairns group proposal to the ministers attending the meeting, but said he got little response from the eec or the united states
u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said the cairns group proposal focused too much on short-term reforms
that's not good enough for us,'' yeutter said, adding that the united states soon would release an official reaction to the plan
willy de clercq, the eec commissioner for external affairs, said the cairns group proposal might present ``an opening'' for further negotiations. ``there should be a way to find common ground,'' he told reporters
although on the substantive level no progress was made, eveybody seems willing to continue working to resolve the issue,'' de clercq said
failure to reach some agreement on agriculture policy by december, when trade ministers will assess progress at the half-way mark in the current round of trade talks, would be disastrous, duffy said
west german economics minister martin bangemann described the mood among the ministers as excellent and said ministers had agreed that a number of issues would be ready for ``early harvest'' by the mid-term review in montreal in december
the ministers decided to meet for more informal talks early in october in pakistan, bangemann said
they agreed to improve gatt's surveillance of world trade practices, as well as its dispute settlement process, and said gatt should encourage greater cooperation with the international monetary fund and the world bank
one suggestion that won strong praise from the ministers was to introduce voluntary arbitration as an alternative to the regular dispute settlement process, bangemann said
the ministers also agreed that trade in textiles should again be governed by gatt regulations once the current multi-fiber agreement expires in 1991, he said. speech as delivered; subs 5th-6th grafs, `when a smoker ...,' with 2 grafs to note that example was given in prepared remarks; it wasn't used in speech. adds 4 grafs at end with poll on increasing use of screening tests.</note>
insurance companies should pay for efforts to detect cancer early in return for slightly higher premiums, the head of the american cancer society said sunday
insurance reimbursement would help primary care doctors to do screening and counseling against cancer, society president harmon eyre told science writers at a society-sponsored conference
in an interview earlier, eyre said he was talking about pap tests for cervical cancer, stool blood tests for colon or rectal cancer, visual examination of the lower colon, called sigmoidoscopy, and breast x-rays called mammograms for breast cancer
in addition, he said, insurors should provide reimbursement for ``health maintenance exams,'' which include counseling about smoking, evaluation of the mouth and lymph nodes for cancer, and discussions about diet, weight control, and self-examination for testicular or breast cancer
when a smoker is treated with antibiotics for pneumonia or bronchitis resulting from smoking, both physican and patient are reimbursed, he said in remarks distributed to science writers
but if that same smoker goes to a physician for counseling about that cigarette habit, no one is reimbursed,'' he said in the remarks. ``it is obviously more productive to prevent health deterioration than to treat it after an illness has begun.''
eyre said in the interview that insurance industry representatives have told the cancer society that expanded coverage would mean higher premiums
some companies have experimented with such policies, he said, but people focus on ``a slight increase in the cost of their health insurance premiums, and their first reaction is, `well, i'm not going to buy that.'''
we haven't convinced the american public they should buy that yet,'' eyre said
i think he's going to have a hard time making that sale,'' said robert waldron, spokesman for the health insurance association of america
insurance premiums rose an average of 15 to 25 percent this year, waldron said in a telephone interview. ``medical costs right now are out of control, and there's a lot of price resistance out there ... for the things that are covered now.''
resistance comes both from individuals and from employers, who buy 90 percent of the nation's health insurance, he said
in the long run, early detection should save money, eyre said. the cost of treating a cancer early is repaid with money saved from treating an advanced case five to 10 years later, he said
a mastectomy to cure an early breast cancer may cost about $5,000, while the cost of caring for a woman who eventually dies of advanced cancer is perhaps $65,000, he said
some health maintenance organizations and prepaid health programs have picked up some screening tests, usually the pap test, eyre said. he said he supports congressional interest in legislation to require medicare to cover mammography and pap testing
that would ``send a major signal'' to the insurance industry, he said
four states _ california, maryland, massachusetts and texas _ require at least some insurance policies to cover mammograms, said kerrie wilson, legislative representative for the cancer society. the massachusetts law also includes pap tests, she said
the society recommends a single mammogram in women between ages 35 and 39, then another mammogram every one or two years up to age 49, and annual mammograms after that
annual pap tests and pelvic examinations are recommended for women 18 or older or who have been sexually active. pap tests can become less frequent after three consecutive satisfactory examinations
for colon and rectal cancer, the society recommends the stool blood test annually after age 50 and sigmoidoscopy every three to five years after that age, following two annual exams with negative results
a poll conducted by the gallup organization for the cancer society at the end of last year found increasing use of screening tests
the poll found that 29 percent of respondents had had a stool blood test, compared to 13 percent in 1976. for sigmoidoscopy, the figure rose from 23 percent in 1983 to 28 percent in 1987
when asked about mammography last year, 52 percent of the women respondents had had a breast x-ray, vs. 41 percent in 1980. for the pap test, 87 percent of the women reported having a test, compared to 53 percent in 1970
the poll included a nationally representative sample of 1,549 adults, and had a margin of error of 4 percent, the society said
brazilian finance minister mailson da nobrega indicated sunday he was confident brazil would get a $1.8 billion ``bridge loan'' from commercial banks to continue interest payments on large portions of its $114 billion foreign debt
i think we're heading towards an agreement,'' da nobrega said after a meeting with osamu yamaguchi, executive director at bank of tokyo's new york main branch
the japanese bank represents brazil's asian creditors
the bridge loan is needed to meet interest payments owed to private banks on more than $68 million in debt for the second quarter of this year. brazil declared a unilateral moratorium last year over payments for that portion of its debt
last february, brazil resumed payments after reaching a basic agreement with its creditor banks on a refinancing package that would include $5 billion in new loans
brazil paid $994 million of its first quarter interest payments but still owes another $270 million to cancel the bill through march. brazil owes another $1.5 billion for the second quarter, da nobrega said saturday
da nobrega, upon arriving in caracas to attend the interamerican development bank annual assembly, said saturday that his country did not have the monetary reserves to cover interest payments for the second quarter
he said brazil needed the short-term bridge loan to help meet those payments while the new refinancing accord is ironed out. brazil wants a 20-year repayment accord plus a grace period of eight years, he said
yamaguchi told reporters that both the creditors and brazil are ``more realistic'' and look for an arrangement ``as soon as possible.''
da nobrega also met with william rhodes, a vice president of citicorp; michael hunter, of lloyds bank; and leighton coleman, of morgan guaranty trust. the brazilian minister said the meetings were ``good and cordial'' but declined to comment further upon them. attorneys</head>
sorting out the millionaire hunt brothers' bankruptcy court cases has required hundreds of attorneys and millions of dollars a month in legal fees for the numerous parties involved, according to a report published sunday
legal costs are estimated at close to $6 million monthly in the multimillion-dollar bankruptcy cases for dallas-based placid oil co. and the estates of william herbert hunt, nelson bunker hunt and lamar hunt, the dallas times herald reported
this is an enormous case requiring an enormous amount of hours to keep up with it,'' said grover hartt, the deputy attorney in charge of the u.s. justice department's tax division office in dallas. ``it is certainly one of the biggest cases our office has ever handled.''
the two bankruptcy cases now involve more than 20 banks, three federal agencies _ the justice department, internal revenue service and securities and exchange commission _ and hundreds of creditors employing armies of attorneys to protect their interests
a master list of parties involved in the placid case includes names of more than 150 different legal firms, said thomas armstrong, an attorney with simon, anisman, doby, wilson &amp; skillern
armstrong, as administrator of the case, sends copies of any developments in the case to everyone on the list
this has been a seven-day-a-week case since it started. just keeping up is the hard part _ we (send) notices to the world every time we do something,'' said armstrong
the william herbert hunt estate has the largest service list with 172 parties, placid is second with 155 and the nelson bunker hunt estate is third with 94, court documents show. documents for the lamar hunt estate were not available
r. paul wickes, an attorney for thompson &amp; knight, which represents first republicbank in its dealings with placid, said the number of lawyers involved is proportionate to the amount of money in question
the number (of lawyers) may be abnormal but there are not many bankruptcies that involve close to $1 billion in assets,'' wickes said. ``it is the kind of case that takes a lot of people putting in a lot of time.''
henry simon, who is the lead counsel representing placid, and other attorneys must submit applications to federal bankruptcy judge harold abramson before being paid. simon estimates he charges $350,000 to $450,000 a month
ed creel, the lawyer representing the william herbert hunt estate, estimates his fees are between $50,000 and $60,000 a month
